<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll of German Train Crash Rises to 70 People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- At least 70 people were killed and 300
others injured, most of them seriously, in Germany's worst train
accident in two decades when a high speed train crashed Wednesday
in a small northern town.
</P>
<P>
Officials in charge of the emergency operation at the scene
said the number of people killed could rise to over 100.
</P>
<P>
The accident happened when a high-speed passenger train
derailed and crashed into a road bridge at 11:10 a.m. at the small
rail station of the northeastern German town of Eschede, reports
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The InterCity-Express (ICE), the country's fastest train,
believed to have first hit a car which had plunged onto the rail
tracks from another road bridge about 100 meters away.
</P>
<P>
The car had reportedly smashed through the crash barrier of the
road bridge and plunged onto the rail tracks in front of the
oncoming train.
</P>
<P>
The train, enroute from Munich to Hamburg, crashed into the car
when traveling at about 200 kilometers per hour, derailed and
smashed into the bridge support.
</P>
<P>
The entire structure of the bridge then collapsed on the top of
the train. The train's 13 carriages were telescoped into one
another, making it difficult for the about 400 rescue workers at
the scene to retrieve those trapped in the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
According to German rail authorities, the train has seats for
759 passengers. But the number of passengers aboard the train is
still unknown.
</P>
<P>
Most of the injured people have been transported by helicopters
to hospitals. Rescue workers said they did not expect to find more
survivors in the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that most of those killed were sitting in the
first four carriages which bore the brunt of the impact.
</P>
<P>
The ICE train is Germany's fastest train with a maximum speed
of up to 280 kilometers an hour. It has never been involved in any
serious accident since being put into use in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
