<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Experts Calm down Fears of Long Lost Uranium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A leading British atomic expert on
Wednesday was trying to calm down fears that a large quantity of
weapons-grade uranium disappeared from a Scottish reprocessing
plant in 1960s.
</P>
<P>
The loss of 170 kg of enriched uranium, enough to make 12
nuclear bombs, was recently disclosed in an official report. It
prompted calls from Scottish anti-nuclear campaigners for the
nuclear plant at Dounreay to be closed down.
</P>
<P>
But John McKeown, chief executive of the British Atomic Energy
Authority in charge of Dounreay, explained that although the
uranium was unaccounted for, it did not necessarily meant it had
been stolen from Dounreay, and could be due to an "accounting
uncertainty."
</P>
<P>
"Let make it clear that material did not disappear in the sense
that it went from the site," McKeown told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said in the late 1960s and early 1970s it had been difficult
to measure accurately how much irradiated material was reprocessed
-- because the plant handled a large number of small pieces from a
wide range of sources -- and how much usable material was
extracted.
</P>
<P>
The missing 170 kg is the difference between the two estimates
-- representing about one percent of the 17 tonnes of material
Dounreay reprocessed, he explained.
</P>
<P>
"Now what I'm telling you is that that was carefully assessed
by scientific experts who were satisfied that that was the cause.
It was looked into very carefully indeed," McKeown said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
