<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Lowers Targeted Growth Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The National Development Council,
the apex body of national planning of Nepal, decided Wednesday to
lower the country's growth rate of GDP to 6.0 percent from 6.5
percent targeted in the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1997-2002).
</P>
<P>
At a meeting chaired by Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala to
review the targets of the ninth plan approach paper, the council
also decided to reduce the total investment to 372.71 billion
rupees (about 6 billion U.S. dollars) from 399.4 billion rupees
(about 6.3 billion dollars) and the total governmental expenditure
has been refixed at 189.58 billion rupees (about 3 billion
dollars) from 215.15 billion rupees (3.4 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The meeting attended by ministers, planners, economists and
representatives of various political parties, was told that the
revision was inevitable due to the internal and external changes
in the economic sector in the past one year.
</P>
<P>
Planners of the present Nepali government regard the target of
6.5 percent GDP growth as "too ambitious."
</P>
<P>
The ninth plan, which accords top priority to poverty
alleviation, should have been implemented last year, but was put
off until this year due to political uncertainty caused by
frequent change of governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
