<HEADLINE> Number of Elephants Down in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The number of elephants has been
decreasing in Nepal for the last few decades due to poaching, lack
of scientific breeding and lack of technical knowledge about the
raising of calves, Nepal Television reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The number of elephants now stands at about 138 throughout the
country, which amass at the four national parks including the
Royal National Park Chitwan, a wildlife park in the sub-tropical
Terai region of Nepal, the state-owned television said.
</P>
<P>
Efforts being made to increase the number of elephants for the
last 11 years are not very successful. The breeding center
established in 1984 at the Chitwan national park has so far raised
only five elephant calves, according to the television report.
</P>
<P>
The Himalayan kingdom of Nepal is rich in fauna and flora. But
press reports said that poaching of wildlife species has grown
over the years as the most lucrative underground profession, and
the country has become a thriving center for illegal wildlife
trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
