<HEADLINE> Lithuania Defends Plan to Join NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Lithuanian Parliament Speaker
Vytautas Landsbergis told visiting Russian lawmakers Wednesday
that Vilnius' membership in NATO "should not give rise to concern."
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency reported that Landsbergis said the
induction of Lithuania into the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) would lower the danger of a potential conflict with Russia
and enhance European stability.
</P>
<P>
Russia is staunchly opposed to the Baltic states' membership in
the alliance, and has offered them security guarantees.
</P>
<P>
However, Landsbergis told a Russian State Duma delegation that
Vilnius could not accept the security guarantees because it was
not sure that Russia would follow a consistent, democratic path,
Interfax reported in a dispatch from the Lithuanian capital.
</P>
<P>
He said admission into the transatlantic military bloc remained
a foreign policy priority and was supported by all political
parties in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Russian delegation, led by the deputy chairman of the State
Duma's Committee for the Commonwealth of Independent States,
Mikhail Vakulenko, was on a two-day visit to Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will also hold meetings with senior officials in
the Lithuanian Foreign Ministry, the heads of the Lithuanian
parliamentary committees and representatives of the local Russian
community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
