<HEADLINE> Finland's GNP to Grow For Five Years: Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Finland's gross national product
(GNP) is expected to grow by an average of 3.5 percent annually
for the next five years, a research institute forecast Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The figure will exceed the average of European Union countries
and the United States by one percentage point.
</P>
<P>
The growth results from a favorable international economy
environment and the country's austerity measures. Finland will
continue to cut public spending and pursue a policy of low
inflation, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
The forecast said exports will grow by an annual of 5.5 percent
and jobless rate will decline from last year's 12.6 percent to
seven percent in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, Finland has been climbing out of its worst
recession since the World War II and has achieved an average GNP
growth of 3.7 percent for the last five years. In 1997, the growth
was 5.9 percent, the highest in 20 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
