<HEADLINE> S. Africa Reiterates Nuclear Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- South Africa, together with
46 other countries, has again expressed concern at nuclear
testing by India and Pakistan in May.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Wednesday, the South African Department
of Foreign Affairs called on India and Pakistan to immediately
abandon the tests and to settle their differences through dialog.
</P>
<P>
J.S. Selebi, South Africa's representative to the Conference
on Disarmament, read the statement in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
He said the nuclear tests made it more imperative that the
Conference on Disarmament should actively address the issue of
nuclear disarmament and the re-emergence of a nuclear arms race.
</P>
<P>
The Conference on Disarmament is the only multilateral
disarmament negotiating forum of the international community and
plays an important role in negotiations on disarmament.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, along with 22 other states, became new members
of the organization in June 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
