<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Recovers $100m From Failed Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has recovered over 10
billion Naira (about 100 million U.S. Dollars) in debts owed to
failed banks through the Failed Banks Tribunals, according to a
senior bank official.
</P>
<P>
John Ebhodaghe, Managing Director of the Nigeria Deposit
Insurance Corporation (NDIC), disclosed this Tuesday at a
workshop in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the Failed Banks Tribunals have provided the
enabling environment for the quick recovery of bad and
irrecoverable debts.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government promulgated the Decree of Failed Banks
Tribunals in 1994 for the recovery of bad debts owed to the
country's many failed banks, arising from serious corruption and
bad management.
</P>
<P>
Ebhodaghe, however, called for the amendment of the 1994
decree to enable healthy banks to have also the access to
recovering their bad debts at the tribunals.
</P>
<P>
This, he said, was made possible by the recent creation of 10
more failed banks tribunals nationwide.
</P>
<P>
He agreed that the type of debts that should be recovered in
favor of healthy banks should be limited to those debts of which
recoveries have been protracted in the ordinary court for a
period of not less than six months.
</P>
<P>
This classification, Ebhodaghe said, was necessary because a
wholesale recovery of all overdue debts owed to the healthy banks
would lead to moral hazards on the part of the banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Proposes Renewing China's MFN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
proposed Wednesday the renewal of normal trade relations with
China, affirming that his policy is in the U.S. national interest.
</P>
<P>
The president said at the Rose Garden that failure to renew
China's Most-favored Nation (MFN) trade status would damage the
United States' economic and strategic relationship with that
country.
</P>
<P>
It would amount to "turning our back on a fourth of the world
at a time when our cooperation for world peace and security is
specially important in light of the recent events in South Asia,"
the president said.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the heightened tension in South Asia
following nuclear tests by India and Pakistan. Both China and the
United States have explored the nuclear explosions and worked
together to defuse the situation.
</P>
<P>
The Republican-dominant Congress has 30 days to debate over the
proposal, which was put forward amid speculations that the
president might run into a battle with the congressmen over the
Administration's China policy as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The battle is complicated by questions about the
administration's technology transfers to Beijing as well as
investigations in alleged Chinese campaign contributions. Both
China and the U.S. government have denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was joined at the announcement by Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, departing later today for Geneva for a
five-nation meeting, hosted by China, on steps to prevent an
escalation of nuclear tensions in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
"This is an important example of how our engagement with China
serves America's interests, stability in Asia, preventing the
spread of weapons of mass destruction, combating international
crime and drug trafficking, protecting the environment," Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also said that his government would continue to deal
forthrightly with China on contentious issues such as human
rights. "There have clearly been some concrete results as a
result of this engagement as well," he said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. exports to China have tripled over the last decade and now
support over 170,000 American jobs, Clinton said. "But just as
important, trade is a force for change in China, exposing China to
our ideas and our ideals and integrating China into the global
economy."
</P>
<P>
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and the chairmen of four
Senate committees, saying they were "deeply troubled by the
national security implications" of the administration's actions,
released copies of letters to Clinton and Cabinet members seeking
rafts of new documents.
</P>
<P>
The letters requested "any and all documents"in the
administration's custody pertaining to the satellite exports and
Chinese proliferation activities, including phone logs, memos,
tapes and electronic mail.
</P>
<P>
The Republicans have also called on the president to postpone
his visit to China scheduled for June. But the president rejected
the suggestion, while offering to cooperate with the
investigators.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
