<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Needs to Advertize Tourism Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
should pump more funds into advertizing its tourism attractions
overseas so as to maintain its momentum in the development of the
industry, a senior tourism official has said.
</P>
<P>
Acting Managing Director of Tanzania Tourist Board (TTB)
Edward Mbwiga said last week that although the visitors to
Tanzania in 1996 rose by 60 percent and foreign exchange earnings
grew by 168 percent over 1992's figures, the country has been
doing the least in tourism promotion compared with Kenya, South
Africa and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Limited funding for tourism promotion abroad could make it
difficult for Tanzania to realize its objective of attracting
500,000 tourists annually by the year 2000, Mbwiga said.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by Financial Times Wednesday, the TTB
acting chief said that 520,000 U.S. Dollars were allocated to the
board in fiscal year 1993/94 to promote the country's attractions
abroad, while Kenya spent 10 million U.S. Dollars for the same
purpose.
</P>
<P>
Mbwiga said that the rise of the private sector role in
tourism made the government further cut spending on tourism
during fiscal year 1995/96, while in Kenya the official
disbursement witnessed a rise.
</P>
<P>
Only 89 million Shillings (about 15,000 U.S. Dollars) were
allocated for the purpose in fiscal year 1996/97, he lamented.
</P>
<P>
The official wondered why the government is collecting money
under the Tourism Development Fund for which a 20 percent hotel
levy is being charged but with most of it being spent on other
sectors.
</P>
<P>
Last year, some 3.4 billion Shillings were collected from the
levy while funding for TTB remained at 89 million Shillings. This
indicate that the fund has a general revenue objective rather
than tourism promotion, Mbwiga said.
</P>
<P>
To attain the tourism goal by 2000, he said, it is essential
for the government to print and distribute brochures and
magazines in more than five languages.
</P>
<P>
Brochures currently in circulation are in English and French,
while an important part of the European market exists in Italy,
Spain and Germany. Therefore, tourism publications in these
languages should as well be prepared, he said.
</P>
<P>
Brochures in Japanese are also needed, he added.
</P>
<P>
The official said in 1992 the country recorded 202,000 tourist
arrivals with earnings amounting to 120 million U.S. Dollars. The
figures climbed to 323,000 arrivals with earnings of 322 million
U.S. Dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Were the country to realize the goal of attracting 500,000
visitors by the year 2000, earnings would climb up to 595 million
U.S. Dollars, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
