<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Varsity Closed After Student Unrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The University of Zimbabwe (UZ),
the largest higher institution in the country, has been closed
indefinitely after violent demonstrations and class boycott.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference at the UZ campus Tuesday in
Harare, Vice-Chancellor Graham Hill said since last Thursday some
students had been demonstrating in the city center peacefully but
Monday became violent, leading to the destruction of property
both in town and at the campus.
</P>
<P>
Hill was quoted by the Zimbabwe News Agency Wednesday as
saying that "this wave of destruction continued on campus last
night resulting in the damage to property and the looting of a
supermarket at the students services center."
</P>
<P>
"I am also informed and actually witnessed that students,
particularly female students, were threatened, harassed and
intimidated and that a number of them left the campus in fear,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Hill said that even after this destruction, the students
resolved to continue with the demonstrations and violence in the
city center Tuesday but the march had been circumvented by the
closure of the university."
</P>
<P>
"It is clear to me that the prevailing climate of disruption
of classes, intimidation and bullying of students and the
destruction of property are not conducive to the continued
teaching and learning operations of the university," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is in these circumstances that I took the decision to
close the university and bar students from entering the campus
until further notice," said hill.
</P>
<P>
He said that three weeks of teaching time had been lost and
all indications pointed to an escalation of violence, threat to
property and a continued boycott of classes.
</P>
<P>
"The closure of the university will enable us to work on
initiatives aimed at bringing back law and order and a return to
normalcy on campus," Hill stressed.
</P>
<P>
He added that students had advanced various reasons for the
unrest including opposition to the privatization of department of
accommodation and catering services, late disbursement of
allowances for some students and the shooting of a student by
police which resulted in a demonstration against police
brutality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
