<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Opens Disaster Response Coordination Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- NATO on Wednesday opened a special
center to coordinate the response to major natural and
technological disasters in Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council
(EAPC) member states.
</P>
<P>
The concept of the disaster response coordination center,
initiated by Russia, was endorsed by the foreign ministers of the
44-nation EAPC last Friday at their half-yearly council meeting in
Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
The Euro-Atlantic Disaster Response Coordination Center
(EADRCC) will be responsible for coordinating, in close
consultation with the United Nations Office for the Coordination
of Humanitarian Affairs, the response of EAPC countries to a
disaster occurring within the EAPC geographical area, said a
senior NATO official responsible for infrastructure, logistics and
civil emergency planning.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the role of the EADRCC is to complement
the leading role of the United Nations in disaster management.
</P>
<P>
The EADRCC is coupled with a Euro-Atlantic Disaster Response
Unit to which EAPC member states voluntarily contribute qualified
personnel of rescue, equipment and materials.
</P>
<P>
Relief can be deployed upon request from the stricken country
or in support of a relevant international organization.
</P>
<P>
The EADRCC is expected to conduct regular training exercises so
as to maximize interoperability among EAPC countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Mining Sector Likely to Remain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's mining sector is likely
to remain depressed as the boost which was expected to come from
platinum is no longer possible due to delays in reaching full
production in Broken Hill Pty (BHP) platinum mine near Harare.
</P>
<P>
In the latest African Business quarterly released Tuesday,
Standard Chartered Bank said little growth would be realized in
the mining sector, which had been expected to recover on the back
of platinum sales this year.
</P>
<P>
"Hopes that platinum production would boost the mining sector
this year have been dashed as the start-up date for full
production at the Hartely Mine has been pushed back toward the
end of 1999," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The Hartely Platinum Mine is one of the largest platinum mine
in the world.
</P>
<P>
It added that although gold production was projected to rise
in volume, it would fall in hard currency, while asbestos, nickel
and ferrochrome were all being affected by low prices.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is the third largest gold producer in Africa after
South Africa and Ghana.
</P>
<P>
Last week Australian mining giant BHP, the joint promoters of
Zimbabwe's first platinum mine, said the mine was still
experiencing production problems and full output could only be
expected at the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Current ore output was only around 57,000 tons a month
compared with the target of 180,000 tons, while the mine was
already more than a year behind its original deadline for full
production.
</P>
<P>
However, the bank noted that business sentiment had improved
slightly following the goverment's move to revise its land reform
program and the belated launch of the second phase of economic
reforms (1996-2000). 
</P>
</TEXT>
