<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Political Factions Urged to Speak Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Majlis (Parliament) Speaker
Ali Akbar Nateq Nouri here Wednesday called on political factions
to speak in line with principles of the Islamic revolution and
guard against those "who want to fish in the troubled water."
</P>
<P>
Addressing a Majlis open session, Nouri, a conservative who
lost last year's presidential elections to Mohammad Khatami, said
that "unity of expression is essential for revolutionary forces."
</P>
<P>
He urged all factions to avoid settling accounts with their
rivals through the Majlis tribune, and assured that there is no
fundamental disagreement among high ranking officials and heads of
the three branches of the country.
</P>
<P>
He warned that there are people in the country antagonistic to
the Islamic Revolution - they want to sow discord, and try to make
others believe that there are disputes among the leadership.
</P>
<P>
He blamed that factional struggle "encourages the enemies to go
on with their plots and schemes" and sometimes wrong performance
or analyses as well as improper statements make the enemies
hopeful.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Commander of the Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps
Rahim Safavi also warned of the existence of "the third force" in
the country which "is at work to undo what the nation has
achieved."
</P>
<P>
The head of the elite army threatened upcoming crack-down. "We
allow them to establish groups and newspapers, but we will deal
with them at an appropriate time and we pick the fruit when it is
mellow," he was quoted as saying in a student gathering at Tehran
University.
</P>
<P>
Without specifying, the commander said the third force relies
on outsiders, aims to destroy the foundation of the religion of
the country, and is even collecting arms.
</P>
<P>
"We are fully aware of that and respond arms with arms," he
said, "when time comes we will expose foreign powers behind these
masks."
</P>
<P>
Safavi's remarks came as political struggle between the
conservatives and moderates became white-hot, with supporters of
both sides staging demonstrations that sometimes culminated in
violence and clashes.
</P>
<P>
The conservatives accuse Khatami, the moderate president who
advocates more freedom and democracy in the country, of moving
away from the values and principles of the Islamic Revolution,
which topple the late shah's regime in 1979.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that some hardliners in the conservative faction
are trying to resort to force against their rivals.
</P>
<P>
Top leaders, including the president and the supreme leader,
have called on the political factions to set aside differences and
close ranks to serve the Islamic system by "allowing different
tastes and points of view." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
