<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Canadian Children Have No Dad at Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Not only are children living through their parents' separation
at a younger and younger age, they also are over-whelmingly ending
up living with their mothers, often with intermittent or no
financial support from their fathers.
</P>
<P>
The children most likely to suffer family breakup are those
born to parents living common-law, according to figures released
Tuesday from Statistics Canada's National longitudinal Survey of
Children and Youth.
</P>
<P>
By the time they are 10 years old, 63 percent of children whose
parents lived common-law have seen their parents separate,
compared with only 14 per cent of children whose parents were
married.
</P>
<P>
The survey looks at 10-and-11-years-old children, so the latest
figures reflect those born in 1987 and 1988.
</P>
<P>
It found that one in five children now in that age group
experienced the breakup of their parents by the time they were five
years old.
</P>
<P>
Four years earlier, the one in five figure wasn't reached until
the age of six. In the early 1970s, it was age 11 and in the early
1960s it was age 16.
</P>
<P>
"Not only has separation and divorce among parents increased in
frequency over the past few decades, but it is occurring earlier
and earlier in the lives of children," the survey said.
</P>
<P>
Most children -- 86 percent -- live with their mother after
separation, the survey reported. Only 7 percent live with their
father. Six percent live in a shared-custody arrangement (going
back and forth), and one percent live in another type of custody
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
For one in three children, the separated parents do not have a
financial-support agreement.
</P>
<P>
And when there is no such agreement, the survey found, there
often isn't much contact either -- half of children whose support
isn't spelled out by court order or agreement see their
non-custodial parent less than once a month.
</P>
<P>
When there is an agreement or order, support isn't necessarily
paid -- the survey found such payment are made regularly or with
only occasional delays for just 6 out of 10 children.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Maintain Baseline Force in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 3 (Xinhua ) -- The United States has said
that it will keep a strong military presence in the Gulf region to
secure the regional stability.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Kuwait News Agency and Kuwait TV Tuesday
night, U.S. Undersecretary of State for Political Affairs Thomas
Pickering said that his country has maintained a baseline force in
the Gulf for years after the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
"What we will be doing is creating a higher level of baseline
force, which will include more aircraft carriers and more missiles
in the region than ever before," Pickering said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S. will maintain a rapid reinforcement
capacity in the Gulf to contain Iraq.
</P>
<P>
U.S.-led multinational forces drove Iraqi troops out of Kuwait
in the Gulf War. Since then the U.S. has maintained a military
presence in the Gulf to allegedly guarantee peace and stability in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Pickering denied that some Arab allies in the region have asked
the U.S. to reduce its armed forces in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
He said it is important to understand that American forces are
stationed in the Gulf for the common interests and common efforts
of the U.S. and Gulf Arab countries to make sure that Iraq will
not succeed in its weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official said that economic sanctions on Iraq will be
lifted until the country fully comply with the United Nations
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed the trade embargo, banning
export of oil, the main revenue earner, on Iraq in 1990 after its
invasion of Kuwait. The world organization will lift the sanctions
only after Iraq proves that it has destroyed its nuclear, chemical
and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
On the sufferings of the Iraqi people, Pickering said that the
U.S. will continue to work with the U.N. on the oil-for-food
deal and make sure the Iraqi people have food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food program reached between the U.N. and Iraq in
1996 allows Iraq to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars of oil over six
months to buy food and medicine for the Iraqi people. The U.N. has
decided to increase the amount of oil Iraq can sell to 5.2 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Pickering arrived here on Tuesday after a trip to Jordan for a
two-day visit in a Middle East tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
