<HEADLINE> Mandela, Masire Hope for Strengthened Democracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela and former Botswanan president Ketumile Masire
Wednesday expressed the hope that Zambian President Federick
Chiluba would take new measures to strengthen democracy in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a lunch with visiting Masire in Cape Town,
Mandela dismissed reports that he had played a central role in
brokering the withdrawal of coup charges against Chiluba's
predecessor, Kenneth Kaunda.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, who was arrested on Christmas Day last year on
suspicion of involvement in a coup plot, found himself a free man
on Monday after charges against him were withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Chiluba had agreed to withdraw the
charges on condition that Mandela persuaded Kaunda to quit active
politics.
</P>
<P>
"The release of (former) President Kaunda from detention is
the initiative of one man -- one man only -- and that is
President Chiluba," Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Kaunda's release was "in response to what
I've done, is not very accurate", he said, adding that Masire and
former Tanzanian president Julius Nyerere had played an even
greater role in disucssing the matter with Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said he hoped that Kaunda, as the father of Zamiban
independence, would be able to recognize the importance of
stepping down from party politics and "try to help Chiluba in
uniting the country".
</P>
<P>
Masire decribed the withdrawal of charges against Kaunda "as a
great thing", saying "We all feel relieved that President Chiluba
has taken this stop and we hope from now on postive things will
follow." 
</P>
