<HEADLINE> Economist Sees Healthy Arab Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Most Arab economies registered
healthy growth rates for the third consecutive year in 1997, an
Arab economist said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ma'Moum Hassan, director general of the Kuwait-based Arab
Institute for Investment Guarantees, said it is expected that the
economies will continue to grow due to many factors, such as
economic reform policies, growing role of the private sector and
the increasing flow of foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
According to the Kuwait News Agency, Hassan said his institute
was following key financial, economic and legislative developments
in the countries, and concluded that these factors have bolstered
investments.
</P>
<P>
Investments increased by 6.8 percent last year compared with
1996, the economist said. Good financial and monetary policies
resulting in lowering inflation have contributed to the growth, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Hassan said the gross domestic product (GDP) of eight Arab
countries out of 19 grew between 4 and 8.5 percent. However, the
GDP of Morocco fell due to a poor agriculture yield, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hassan said inflation rates in 17 countries out of 19 were
under the 10 percent margin in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
