<HEADLINE> NATO Sends New Inspectors to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- NATO delayed a decision on sending
allied troops to Albania but only decided on Wednesday to send
another inspection team to the Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana told reporters while
inaugurating the Euro-Atlantic Disaster Response Coordination
Center that it was the only decision the weekly North Atlantic
Council meeting took.
</P>
<P>
The council is the policy maker of the 16-nation western
military alliance.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief said that the alliance had to wait for the team
to return and report on its findings before making further moves.
</P>
<P>
But Solana said that NATO is very concerned about the current
situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
NATO has sent several inspection teams to Albania in the past
few weeks, mostly to gauge the country's infrastructure for coping
with the possible influx of refugees.
</P>
<P>
NATO foreign ministers decided at their last week council
meeting to study the possibility of a preventive deployment of
between 7,000 and 23,000 troops to help guard the northern border
of Albania to fend off any spillover of the violence from
neighboring Yugoslavia's province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
NATO defense ministers are meeting in Brussels next week and
they are expected to focus on the alliance action in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Press reports claimed that thousands of refugees were moving on
the Kosovo side of the hills separating the Yugoslavia province
and Albania.
</P>
<P>
Solana said that the newly-opened Euro-Atlantic Disaster
Response Coordination Center may be of help if the refugee problem
deteriorates along the Kosovo-Albania borders.  
</P>
</TEXT>
