<HEADLINE> Half Cypriot Children Face Overweight: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus on Wednesday stressed the
need to improve children's diet because an alarming number of them
are facing the health problem of overweight.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted by the Cypriot ministries of health and
education showed that 53 percent of the country's children in the
11 to 12 age group have cholesterol levels above the recommended
threshold.
</P>
<P>
Tests on 11,000 children at the ages have revealed that 46
percent of the girls and 34 percent of the boys are overweight,
while 6 percent of the girls and 16 percent of the boys are obese.
</P>
<P>
Only half of the Cypriot children have the proper weight for
their height.
</P>
<P>
The survey aimed to give general health information to children
who took part, as well as individual attention attention to each
child.
</P>
<P>
Michalis Tormaritis, a specialist of Greek University of Crete,
who took part in the survey, warned that children in Cyprus
consume more calories than anywhere else in the world.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot Health Minister Christos Solomis said that children's
diet needs improvement. He called for healthy eating habits which
must filter down through the family. 
</P>
</TEXT>
