<HEADLINE> Ghana to Review Law System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Ghanaian government is to
undertake a comprehensive review of the country's laws to bring
them up-to-date, Attorney-General and Minister of Justice Obed
Asamoah has said.
</P>
<P>
Asamoah was quoted by the latest edition of the
London-published West Africa magazine as saying that some of the
laws in Ghana have been amended so often that "one is not too
certain what the current state of the law is."
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that the value to the country of such an
up-to-date state the laws of the land is immeasurable, for it
provides a precise state of the laws, easy and ready
accessibility and shows areas that truly need attention," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is to cost five million U.S. Dollars, will
take off in January next year and last for five years, the report
said. 
</P>
