<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Praises Chirac's Comments on Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's Muslim group Hezbollah, or
Party of God, Wednesday praised French President Jacques Chirac's
recent remarks on Israeli withdrawal proposal, saying they could
force Israel to freeze its "manoeuvre" for a while.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General of the Iranian-backed group Sheikh Hassan
Nasrallah said at a religious rally that France's new stance
which he said was initially ambiguous toward Israeli conditional
withdrawal proposal could effectively influence other European
countries and lead to the shelving of it by Israel for a while.
</P>
<P>
During his third visit in two years to Lebanon on May 29-31,
Chirac called on Israel to comply with the United Nations
Resolution 425 without any conditions.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed rejection to any attempt to amend the
resolution for a conditional withdrawal, saying that any change
would have to get the approval of Lebanon beforehand.
</P>
<P>
His remarks triggered scathing reaction from Israel. Israeli
radio quoted a senior official as saying that Israel didn't
impose any preconditions for a pullout and those conditions were
originally included in the resolution.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old resolution calls for an immediate and
unconditional Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon where it set
up a 1,200-square-kilometer so-called security zone in 1985
allegely to protect its northern borders from cross border
attacks.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, Israel formally endorsed the resolution and
offered to withdraw from south Lebanon on condition that Lebanon
provides security guarantee for its north before its pullout.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon rejected the offer, saying it contradicted the
unconditional nature of the resolution.
</P>
<P>
But Israel didn't give up and wanted to go head with its
proposal by amending the resolution.
</P>
<P>
Nasrallah said Israel could stop its manoeuvre for some time
but not permanently as Israel always launches a political
campaign from time to time in a bid to make more troubles.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah is leading a guerrilla war to drive 2,000 Israeli
troops out of south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
