<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Coalition Splits Over Redeployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Moderate and hawkish members of
Israeli coalition traded accusations Wednesday amid reports that
the United States would soon announce its decision on Israeli
troop redeployment on the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Moderate members of the Knesset (Parliament) within the
Likud-led coalition touched off the debate by initializing a
campaign to support Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu over making
the long-delayed decision on the scope of the second redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The moderates, including Likud's Zeev Boim, Yisrael Baaliya's
Roman Bronfman and Alexandre Lubostsky of the Third Way, charged
the far-rightist members for trying to torpedo Netanyahu's effort
to make the decision on the redeployment. They called for a full
coalition meeting next week to show support for the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to the Knesset, Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai, widely-considered the leading dove in the coalition,
came out again for an agreement with the Palestinian side. The
minister, who held talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in
Cairo Tuesday, declared that "it's high time to decide on the
second redeployment."
</P>
<P>
The Far-right members rejected the charge and accused the
moderates of weakening the prime minister in the midst of the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Nisan Slominavsky, of the far-rightist National Religious
Party (NRP), said it was "unbelievable" that the moderates asked
Netanyahu to give up more while he was facing pressure from the
U.S. administration. "I can't understand them," he said.
</P>
<P>
The NRP faction, which owns nine of 61 coalition seats in the
Knesset, has insisted that it would topple the government if
Netanyahu agrees to withdraw from more than 9 percent of the West
Bank. If Netanyahu gave up more land, some coalition members would
"vote against him," Slominavsky said.
</P>
<P>
Tension within the coalition flared up at a time when
Netanyahu was reportedly trying to wrap up an agreement with the
Palestinians over the second withdrawal in the West
Bank. Netanyahu said that once he had a "good deal," he would
move forward regardless of opposition inside his own coalition.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the prime minister was planning to combine
the three stages of redeployment into a 15 percent pullback, and
if it was accepted by the U.S. and the Palestinians, he would
make further concessions.
</P>
<P>
But the government is likely to fall if Netanyahu fails to
convince the hawkish coalition members to support him when the
redeployment decision is put to vote in the Knesset. The
government is now holding the minimum majority of 61 seats in the
120-member Knesset.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that, if the opposition Labor Party refuses to
provide a safety net for Netanyahu on the pullback issue, the fall
of the government and the holding of new elections would be
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. Ambassador to Israel Edward Walker said
Wednesday that he expected a decision to be made "very soon" on
the U.S. compromise proposal for a 13 percent pullback. Speaking
after his talks with Labor leader Ehud Barak in Tel Aviv, he
stressed that a decision should be made within days, not weeks.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has threatened to make public the widely leaked but
never publicized plan and openly blame Israel for its failure to
break the impasse in the peace process if it rejects the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Previous reports said U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
had set an unofficial deadline for Netanyahu to submit Israel's
ultimate redeployment plan to Washington by the end of this week,
if not sooner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
