<HEADLINE> Lebanon, Not Israel, Needs Security Guarantees: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri said on Wednesday that it is Lebanon, not Israel, that
needs security guarantees.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Egyptian Ahram Abdu newspaper, Hariri
said that Israel does not need security guarantees because it
possesses nuclear weapons and powerful armed forces, with which it
occupies Lebanon's territory.
</P>
<P>
Israel has never officially confirmed it has nuclear weapons,
but foreign experts estimate that it has stockpiled 200 nuclear
bombs.
</P>
<P>
Hariri was referring to an Israeli demand that the two
countries negotiate security arrangements before Israel withdraws
from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in 1985 in
south Lebanon to allegedly protect its northern areas from
cross-border attacks by Lebanese Muslim guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, the Jewish state decided to endorse the United
Nations Security Council Resolution 425, which calls for
unconditional Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But it attached its troop pullback to Lebanon's security
guarantees for its northern areas.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has rejected the offer, insisting the withdrawal be
unconditional.
</P>
<P>
Hariri called on European Union countries to pressure Israel to
carry out the relevant U.N. resolutions and adhere to its
commitments to push forward the Middle East peace process.
</P>
