<HEADLINE> More Than 100 Bodies Recovered after German Train Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ESCHEDE, Germany, June 3 (Xinhua) -- More than 100 bodies have
been recovered from the wreckage of a German high-speed train
which derailed and crashed into a bridge Wednesday morning in the
northeastern German town of Eschede, rescue officials said.
</P>
<P>
The death toll was expected to rise further, said officials of
the emergency rescue center on the scene.
</P>
<P>
The accident, which is believed to be the most serious one in
modern German history, happened when the InterCity Express (ICE)
train derailed and crashed into a nearby road bridge at 11:10 a.m.
at the small rail station of Eschede.
</P>
<P>
Earlier media reports said the train, enroute from Munich to
Hamburg, was derailed after hitting a car which had plunged onto
the rail tracks after a road accident.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman, however, said the automobile concerned had
actually parked on the bridge and fallen onto the ground after the
bridge collapsed due to the train crash.
</P>
<P>
The first four carriages of the train were telescoped into one
another and wedged under the damaged bridge. Rescue workers are
still unable to reach two of the wagons at the moment.
</P>
<P>
According to German rail authorities, the train has seats for
759 passengers. But the actual number of passengers aboard the
train is still unknown.
</P>
<P>
A fleet of 15 helicopters have been deployed to transport the
injured to nearby hospitals. About 400 rescue workers, soldiers
and policemen are busy on the scene.
</P>
<P>
The ICE train is Germany's fastest train with a maximum speed
of up to 280 kilometers an hour. It has never been involved in any
serious accident since being put into use in 1991.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
