<HEADLINE> Chirac Calls on Russia to Modernize Financial System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
Wednesday called on Russia to modernize its financial system as
one way to re-obtain confidence of foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with visiting Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko in the Elysee palace, Chirac said that the financial
crisis which has struck Russia is causing French concern, said
presidential spokeswoman Catherine Colonna.
</P>
<P>
"It seems necessary...to establish a stable financial framework
in Russia, which will improve the fiscal collection, create a
modern and transparent banking system, and a legal and fiscal
framework, to give confidence to investors," said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his confidence in the "capacity of Russia to
bring to a satisfactory conclusion its policy of reforms."
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko, who arrived here Wednesday on his first visit abroad
since taking office in April, said that Russia is determined to
carry through its reform programs and implement the "emergency and
drastic measures" adopted by his government.
</P>
<P>
He thanked France and other members of the Group of Seven most
industrialized nations for their support to Russia, but described
the decision by International Monetary Fund to send 670 million
U.S. dollars of financial aid to Russia as "psychological" rather
than substantial support.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko also called for equal access to the international
market, especially the markets in the European Union countries, by
Russian products, and an elimination of "discriminatory
constraints" in trade.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Chirac also called on Russia to use its
influence on Serbia to help solve the crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko will co-chair on Thursday with his French counterpart
Lionel Jospin a session of the 4th Franco-Russian Commission of
Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
French and Russian officials will discuss the establishment of
an assembly plant by the French automaker Renault in Moscow, as
well as cooperations in nuclear energy, oil, outer space
exploration and aeronautics, and agriculture and food processing
industry.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for Moscow on Thursday, Kiriyenko will also meet
with French entrepreneurs to persuade them to increase investments
in Russia.
</P>
<P>
French investments in Russia stand between 200 and 400 million
U.S. dollars, according to different calculating systems of the
two countries.  
