<HEADLINE> Rains Slow Down ECOMOG Operation in S. Leone: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Rains are slowing down efforts by
the west African peace-keeping force ECOMOG to close in on the
remnants of the forces loyal to ousted junta leader Johnny Paul
Koromah in Sierra Leone, ECOMOG official said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking with newsmen at the Lagos airport on his way to
Abuja, ECOMOG commander Timothy Shelpidi said
Wednesday that ECOMOG troops have been unable to move as fast as
they did when they began the operation in February.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG entered Sierra Leone soon after Koromah's coup last May
and had succeeded in driving out Koromah from capital Freetown in
February, thus making its possible for elected President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah to resume his power in March.
</P>
<P>
The peace-keeping force has since then been trying to mop up
the remnants of Koromah's forces throughout Sierra Leone
especially in the northern and eastern parts.
</P>
<P>
Shelpidi said the junta forces have run short of ammunition
and supplies and have restored to attacking innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
"The unfortunate thing about this incident is that they have
unleashed lot of atrocities on innocent villagers, seizing their
livestock, foodstuff and raping women," he said.
</P>
<P>
Shelpidi called on the international community to assist
ECOMOG to solve its logistic problems, including airlifting its
troops and provision of helicopters and vehicles.
</P>
<P>
He added that about 75 percent of the equipment used by ECOMOG
in its eight years of peace-keeping mission in Liberia have been
moved to Sierra Leone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
