<HEADLINE> U.N. Inspectors Continue Search for Iraqi Warheads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 3 (Xinhua) -- United Nations weapons inspectors
Wednesday continued to excavate the warheads that Iraq destroyed
and buried after the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Nils Carlstrom, director of Baghdad Monitoring and Verification
Center of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM), said in a
statement that a survey team of the commission is to find out the
number of the warheads.
</P>
<P>
But Carlstrom did not say how many warheads the team has
uncovered.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM is charged with overseeing the elimination of Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction, namely nuclear, chemical and
biological weapons as well as long-range missiles.
</P>
<P>
Only when UNSCOM certifies that Iraq has destroyed the banned
weapons, will the U.N. Security Council lift the economic
sanctions imposed in 1990 after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait, which
triggered the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Iraq says it has destroyed all the chemical and biological
warheads. But the U.N. says it will not take its words. The work
of the team, which arrived here two weeks ago and will finish its
mission by June 18, will help UNSCOM verify Iraq's claims.
</P>
<P>
Of Iraq's weapons files, the missile and nuclear files are near
closing. 
</P>
