<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat in Oman to Push for Arab Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
arrived in Omani capital Muscat Wednesday to continue his push for
holding an Arab summit to discuss the stalled Israeli-Palestinian
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the airport, Arafat lashed out at Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu for violating the signed
agreements with the Palestinan National Authority (PNA), according
to reports reaching here from Muscat.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said the agreements signed by the two sides were
international ones signed under the aegis of the United States and
Russia, and with mediation by the European Union, Norway, Egypt,
and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The PNA president said the Middle East peace process is
experiencing hard times due to the hardline policies adopted by
the Israeli government. "This visit comes in the middle of hard
times for the peace process because of the intransigence of
Netanyahu and his government," he said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat was referring to the 15-month deadlock in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process since March 1997 when Israel
started construction of the Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the Israeli-Palestinian dispute centers on the scope
of the second phase of Israeli troop withdrawal in the West
Bank. Israel has until now rejected a U.S. proposal calling for a
13 percent pullback, which has been accepted in principle by the
PNA.
</P>
<P>
By proposing to convene an Arab summit, Arafat attempts to
increase the pressure on the Israeli government to prevent further
delay in carrying out the second redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Before his visit to Oman, Arafat had already traveled to
Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates. During his stay in
Oman, the Palestinian leader is expected to meet Sultan Qaboos Bin
Said to discuss latest developments of the peace process and
to coordinate the Arab stance toward Israel.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is also expected to visit other Arab states, including
Jordan and Sudan to continue lobbying support for holding an Arab
summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
