<HEADLINE> Extra Holiday for Britons to Mark New Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LONDON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Britons will be able to take the day
off on New Year's Eve 1999 as the government granted an extra
public holiday for the Millennium.
</P>
<P>
Culture, Media and Sport Secretary Chris Smith said in a
statement to parliament that the extra holiday, which falls on
Friday, will give people the weekend and the Monday bank holiday to
recover from the New Year celebrations.
</P>
<P>
"I know that large numbers of people will welcome this
opportunity to prepare for the festivities on New Year's Eve and
New Year's Day 2000," Smith said.
</P>
<P>
The period around the end of the year already provides many
Britons with an extended midwinter break.
</P>
<P>
Christmas Day, the following day, known in Britain as Boxing
Day, and New Year's Day are already public holidays and workers
get days off in lieu if they fall at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Smith said a government consultation exercise had shown
"overwhelming support" for the extra holiday on the last day of
the second millennium.  
</P>
</TEXT>
