<HEADLINE> European Shares Sharply up on Good Company Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
sustained Tusday's gains and ended sharply higher Wednesday, with
Paris hitting a new record closing high, boosted by
better-than-expected company earnings and good performance in some
stocks.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE-100 index of leading shares on the London market ended
56.1 points or nearly one percent higher at 5,898.4, only a shade
below the 5,900 level, encouraged by a strong performance in other
major European bourses.
</P>
<P>
However, volumes remained light as investors kept to the
sidelines ahead of Thursday's Bank of England interest rate
decision.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Railtrack shares rose comfortably on the
back of strong results and government plans to complete the
long-delayed high-speed rail link between London and the Chunnel
tunnel.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares closed 30.98 points or 0.55 percent
up at 5,613.76 on the DAX-30 index, due to positive interest rate
outlook and signs of improving confidence in the Russian economy,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
The market was also inspired by the better-than-expected first
quarter earnings figures released by Deutsche Telekom AG and
market optimism that Volkswagen AG would do the same at Thursday's
shareholders' meeting.
</P>
<P>
On the Paris bourse, the CAC-40 index closed at a new record
high at 4,149.37, up 62.39 points or 1.53 percent as late buying
pushed the index sharply higher.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that a scarcity of sellers in the market induced
buyers to propel prices up.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, positive sentiment in the pharmaceutical, auto and
retail sectors also gave the market strong support, but there was
also some profit-taking in some stocks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
