<HEADLINE> Tonnes of Explosives Stolen in New Brunswick </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Thieves made off with nearly two
tonnes of explosives in the Canadian province of New Brunswick,
police said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The thieves broke into a storage area of a gravel pit in the
city of Moncton around May 28 and stole a large amount of dynamite
sticks and detonators.
</P>
<P>
The provincial police has made a plea for help to track down
the stolen explosives, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Police fear that the explosives could end up in the hands of
criminals groups and endanger the society.
</P>
<P>
Over the past six weeks, three explosive devices were found in
the city Saint John, about an hour's drive from Moncton.
</P>
<P>
One bomb blew up outside a provincial police station and
another two unexploded ones were discovered outside a courthouse
and jail.
</P>
<P>
The provincial judicial system is being targeted for
retaliation by local drug traffickers, the reports said.  
</P>
