<HEADLINE> Lesotho Forms New Cabinet, Former FM Dumped  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Two leading members of the
ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD) have been left out of
Lesotho Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The two figures are the younger brother of former prime
minister Ntsu Mokhehle, Shakhane Mokhehle, and the party's
national chairman and former foreign minister Kelebone Maope.
</P>
<P>
Among the new faces is Mokhehle's former special adviser, Tom
Thabane, who replaces Maope as foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
The radio said the new ministers were appointed by King Letsie
III, on the advice of Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili, South
African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Maope, the second most prominent figure after Mosisili in the
LCD, had been considered a challenger of Mosisili for the post of
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Mosisili has three portfolios -- prime minister, minister of
defense and minister of public service.
</P>
<P>
Two portfolios -- minister of works and transport and minister
of agriculture, cooperatives and land reclamation -- were not
filled.
</P>
<P>
There had been some restructuring of portfolios, including the
establishement of the Ministry of Environment, Women and Youth
Affairs. This will be handled by the only female member of the
cabinet, Mamoshebi Kabi.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet will be sworn in by the king at the Basutho Royal
Palace in Maseru Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
The names of Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili, and Leketekete
Ketso, minister of finance and development planning, Mopshatla
Mabitle, minister of local government and home affairs, Tom
Thabane, minister of foreign Affairs are found in the 14 members
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet was formed after the LCD won a sweeping victory in
the May 23 general election. 
</P>
