<HEADLINE> India, Pakistan Incline to Talk: Iran's FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi said Wednesday that India and Pakistan have agreed in
principle to restart negotiations to reduce tension following
their nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
"In my talks with both Pakistani and Indian officials, we
arrived at a conclusion that the two sides showed interest in
waning tension in the region and also agreed in principle to
restart their negotiations," Kharrazi said on his return from a
three-day visit to Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Republic News Agency quoted him as saying that
officials of two countries desired to see that all issues,
including the Kashmir issue, would be on the agenda of the
negotiations, and no nuclear test would be conducted until results
of their talks are finalized.
</P>
<P>
The atmosphere is conducive for Indian-Pakistani serious and
comprehensive talks, Kharrazi said, adding there are also positive
signs that the two would agree to sign on to the Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty.
</P>
<P>
He said he would present the results of his talks with Indian
and Pakistani officials to the disarmament conference in Geneva,
but rejected media reports that he was mediating between Islamabad
and New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Iran's stance, Kharrazi said Tehran does not
encourage the procurement and manufacturing of nuclear weapons and
it is not at all interested in doing so.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, it is a reality that Pakistan has nuclear
power capability, and it is quite natural that when an Islamic
country is in possession of nuclear capability, such a factor
would contribute to it being a deterrent to Israel which has
similar weapons.
</P>
<P>
"Iran does not have any plan absolutely for the acquisition of
nuclear weapon, but on the contrary, Iran wants to see that
nuclear disarmament program become effective," he said.
</P>
<P>
Iran believes the region should initially be a non-nuclear zone
and the world become fully free of any nuclear weapons, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
