<HEADLINE> N.Irish Policing Commission Members Named </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Britain named an international
commission Wednesday which is responsible for restructuring the
Northern Irish police force under the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The commission is headed by Chris Patten, the former Hong Kong
governor, and made up of seven members. They include professors,
lawyers and crime experts from Britain, Canada and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The commission has been established under a historic accord
approved by voters last month which saw policing reforms as a key
element in reducing tension in the British province.
</P>
<P>
Patten, the commission chairman, pledged in a statement that
the commission would consult widely and report by a deadline of
summer 1999.
</P>
<P>
During decades of guerrilla war and sectarian strife, policing
in Northern Ireland has been a divisive issue between majority
Protestants who owe allegiance to Britain and minority Catholics
who want to end British rule.
</P>
<P>
The Royal Ulster Constabulary, the 13,000-strong police force,
is dominated by pro-British Protestants and is viewed with
hostility by the Catholics who wish to see a united Irish island.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein, the political arm of the outlawed Irish Republican
Army (IRA), and one of the signatories to the peace accord, wants
the RUC disbanded.
</P>
<P>
Britain however says there is no question of abolishing the
force, which has lost some 300 members mostly in IRA guerrilla
attacks.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister stressed Tuesday while visiting Belfast
that the Northern Ireland police force will not be disbanded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
