<HEADLINE> Balkan FMs' Meeting to Be Held in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministers of the Balkan
countries are due to gather Turkey's largest city of Istanbul on
June 8 to 9 to discuss regional security and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo issue and the establishment of the Southeastern
European Multinational Peace Troops will be high on the agenda, a
Turkish Foreign Ministry statement said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Albania, Bulgaria, Macedonia, Romania, the Yugoslav Federation,
Greece as well as Turkey will participate in the conference.
Foreign ministers from Bosnia-Herzegovina and Croatia will be
present as observers.
</P>
<P>
The massive bloody clashes between the Serbian police and
ethnic Albanians living in Kosovo, Yugoslavia have caused grave
concern among the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
The ethnic Albanians are seeking independence from the
Yugoslav Federation but the request has been rejected by
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Some Balkan states such as Turkey and Bulgaria have called for
the formation of a multinational peace-keeping force, whose duty
is to maintain peace and stability in the region, a hotbed of
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Besides general discussions, the ministers are also expected
to hold busy bilateral talks during the two-day session.
</P>
<P>
The Istanbul meeting is a follow-up of the Balkan summit in the
Crete island, Greece last year. The Balkan leaders had decided to
further strengthen their political and economic cooperation
through the Balkan summit and the Balkan foreign ministerial
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
