<HEADLINE> Israel, Syria Hold Secret Talks: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Aiming to break the protracted
deadlock in their peace talks, Israeli and Syrian negotiators met
secretly last week in the United States, Israeli state television
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Channel I disclosed that three Israeli and three Syrian
negotiators took part in the four-day meetings in Houston for the
first time in two years. The talks were hosted by former
U.S. Secretary of State James Baker and U.S. Assistant Secretary
of State Martin Indyk, a former U.S. Ambassador to Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian side was represented by Syrian Ambassador to the
U.S. Walid Moualim, and the Israeli delegation led by Uzi Arad,
top diplomatic aide to Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The report added that the Houston talks were aimed at seeking
ways to resume the peace talks between the two countries, which
came to an halt in March 1996.
</P>
<P>
Syria wants to reach a peace treaty with Israel on condition
that Israel returns the strategic Golan Heights captured by Israel
in the 1967 War.
</P>
<P>
Damascus has been demanding the Netanyahu-led government resume
the talks from the point where the talks were left off, namely on
the basis of an informal promise made by former Israeli Labor
government on a total withdrawal from the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
Until now, Netanyahu has publicly rejected the Syrian demand,
insisting that the talks should be resumed without any
conditions. Most parties within his right-wing coalition are
opposed to relinquishing the whole Golan heights, citing
security reasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
