<HEADLINE> Tornadoes, Storms Lash East U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Severe storms and tornadoes
struck eastern part of the United States Tuesday, killing several
people, injuring dozens and destroying hundreds of houses.
</P>
<P>
Severe storms that struck North Carolina to upstate New York
also left tens of thousands of residents without power.
</P>
<P>
The town of Lake Carey in northeastern Pennsylvania was struck
by an apparent tornado Tuesday night. Two people in a mobile home
were killed and nine others injured.
</P>
<P>
A storm at Pittsburgh Tuesday morning destroyed 15 buildings
and damaged 250.
</P>
<P>
Pennsylvania Governor Tom Ridge declared disaster emergencies
Wednesday in nine counties. He said he would decide later whether
to ask for a federal disaster declaration.
</P>
<P>
In Wyoming County, New York, about 25 houses were destroyed and
some 15,000 residents were rendered without power. Fallen trees
and debris also blocked searchers' access to some areas.
</P>
<P>
In western Maryland, three apparent tornadoes struck Frostburg
and nearby areas Tuesday night, damaging some 100 homes, shearing
trees and rupturing gas lines.
</P>
<P>
About 31,000 customers in West Virginia were left without
power by severe thunderstorms. Storms also caused scattered damage
in Virginia and North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
It was the second round of violent weather this week. Five
people were killed in severe storms that swept Massachusetts, New
York, Pennsylvania and Vermont late Sunday and early Monday. That
same storm system caused widespread damage in the Midwest during
the weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
