<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-03 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: Agreement on Pullback to Be Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 3 (Xinhua) -- As Israeli coalition government
splits over the troop pullback from the West Bank, Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu expressed belief Wednesday that an agreement on
the issue will be approved by the Knesset (Parliament).
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Likud ministers, Netanyahu reiterated that the
decision on the pullback, which he did not say when will be
finalized, is "divorced" from coalition considerations, Israel
Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai warned that the
deadlock in the peace process would lead to confrontation and
violence.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the Knesset, Mordechai said both the Israeli
defense forces and the Palestinian National Authority are
preparing for the scenarios.
</P>
<P>
As the United States has threatened to make public its proposal
calling for a 13.1 percent Israeli pullback, tensions were
mounting in the Knesset Wednesday as moderate and far-right
factions of the coalition traded accusations over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Moderate Knesset members touched off the debate by launching a
campaign to support Netanyahu, who they said is moving toward an
agreement with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
They accused rightwingers of trying to torpedo Netanyahu's
effort to take a decision on the withdrawal and called for a
cabinet meeting next week to show their support for the prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
The rightwingers rejected the charge and blamed the moderates
for weakening Netanyahu's position in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Nisan Salominavsky of the National Religious Party said it was
"unbelievable" that the moderates asked Netanyahu to give up more
lands under pressure from the United States. "I can not understand
them," he said.
</P>
<P>
What is agreed upon by the two factions is that the coalition
would fall apart over the issue of troop pullback and the
possibility of an early election is emerging.
</P>
<P>
If Netanyahu agrees to hand over more lands than the
rightwingers can tolerate to the Palestinians, some coalition
members would "vote against him," Salominavsky said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is reportedly trying to reach an agreement with the
Palestinians over Israeli withdrawal. He has said that once he has
a "good deal," he would move forward regardless of opposition
inside his own coalition.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources said that Netanyahu is planning to combine the
three stages of pullback into a single-phase withdrawal from 15
percent of the West Bank, and if it is accepted by the U.S. and
the Palestinians, he might make further concessions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
