<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Albright Outline Goal of Geneva Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said
Wednesday that the U.S. goal at a Geneva meeting is fo work out a
strategy to press India and Pakistan to stop their nuclear arms
race and to build a peaceful stable South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made the remarks after he discussed the South Asian
situation with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and National
Security Adviser Sandy Berger.
</P>
<P>
Albright will leave for Geneva to attend a meeting, scheduled
for Thursday, with the foreign ministers of the five permanent
members of the U.N. Security Council to discuss how to reverse the
arms race in South Asia after India and Pakistan detonated their
nuclear explosions last month.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is to forge a common strategy to move India and
Pakistan back from their nuclear arms race and to begin to build a
more peaceful stable region," Clinton told news conference at Rose
Garden following his meeting with his top foreign policy aides.
</P>
<P>
The president said the United States initiated the Geneva
conference because he believed the nuclear tests conducted by
India and Pakistan were "self-defeating, wasteful and dangerous."
</P>
<P>
They also "stand in stark contrast to the progress the world
had made over the past several years, in reducing stockpiles and
containing the spread of nuclear weapons," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton urged the Senate to quickly approve the Comprehensive
Test Ban Treaty, he signed at the United Nations two years ago, as
the situation in South Asia "makes it all the more important" for
the Senate to debate and vote on the CTBT without delay.
</P>
<P>
"If we're calling other nations to act responsibly, America
must set the example," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton praised China for its vital role for peace in the
region, saying, "Let me express my appreciation to China for
chairing the (Geneva) P-5 meeting to which Secretary Albright is
going."
</P>
<P>
"This is further evidence of the important role China can play
in meeting the challenges of the 21st century, and the
constructive Chinese leadership that will be essential to the
long-term resolutions of issues involving South Asia," he added.
</P>
<P>
Albright set out three concrete goals of the Geneva meeting.
The first is to send a message to India and Pakistan that "there
should be no further nuclear testing, no deployment of testing of
missiles, no more inflammatory rhetoric and no more provocative
military activity."
</P>
<P>
The second is a "longer-term goal," she said. That is to "avert
a regional arms race and to reexamine options for easing the
underlying political problems between India and pakistan,
including Kashmir."
</P>
<P>
"Finally, we will affirm our resolve to bolster the global
nonproliferation regime," Albright said. "This means taking steps
to discourage other countries from following the disastrous
example set by India and Pakistan." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
