<HEADLINE> Wiezsaecker: Europe Will Inevitably Seek Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Former German President Richard Von
Wiezsaecker said here Wednesday that Europe would inevitably seek
political integration after the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Wiezsaecker said political
union would be a continuous process of development.
</P>
<P>
He said that the exclusion of some European Union (EU) member
states from the first wave of EMU would not lead to a two-speed
Europe.
</P>
<P>
The former president praised Greece for its efforts to prepare
the economy for the euro, saying that he was confident that Greece
would meet its target of joining EMU by January 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
As for the EU's enlargement, Wiezsaecker said that candidate
states should adopt certain transition measures concerning the
free movement of people.
</P>
<P>
The issue of free movement of people would influence Turkey's
demand to enter the EU, he said, adding that the German presidency
of the EU would seek a detente in Greece's relations with Turkey.
</P>
