<HEADLINE> Mkapa Urges District Commissioners to Monitor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa has urged district commissioners to be vigilant of
prevailing misconducts of officers at grassroot levels.
</P>
<P>
Opening a seminar for district commissioners in the new
capital of Dodoma Wednesday, Mkapa said he has got reports that a
lot of innocent people have been humiliated by ward and village
executive officers and yet no action has been taken to stop this
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said it is "shocking" to hear that the officers have
joined hands with unscrupulous magistrates and the police to
humiliate common people and confiscate their property.
</P>
<P>
Whast's worse is that some of the district commissioners have
grown aware of the evil acts of their subordinates but took no
actions to stop them.
</P>
<P>
He urged the district commissioners to listen carefully to
people's problems and work out practical solutions, adding that
once the problems are reported to the President's Office, the
district commissioners would be regarded as having failed to
perform their duties.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa also advised the commissioners to hold regular
consultations with common people and exchange ideas with them on
socio-economic development.
</P>
<P>
The President required the district commissioners to conduct
correctly in front of the people they lead because they have the
a responsibility in shaping the society. He said those who are
addictive to alcoholism, use abusive language against others and
conduct promiscuity will be ousted from the government.
</P>
<P>
Responding to reports that some of the district commissioners
use working hours and vehicles for their part-time jobs, the
president warned that this would not be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa also lashed out at the officials who misused people's
contributions and imposed excessive taxes on traders in the
countryside.  
</P>
