<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Productivity Growth Slips Slightly During </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. productivity growth
slipped to an annual rate of 1.1 percent in the first three months
of the year, the Labor Department reported here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate in the productivity of non-farm,
non-supervisory workers was considerably better than the 0.2
percent estimate issued last month, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Still, it represented a slip from the 1.4 percent rate of the
fourth quarter of last year. And it's down considerably from the
1.8 percent average through 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
Productivity measures output per hour of work and is considered
crucial to the improvement of living standards. The last time
Americans enjoyed low inflation and high growth, the 1960s and
early 1970s, productivity growth averaged a phenomenal 2.9 percent
a year.
</P>
<P>
The lapse in first-quarter productivity growth was focused in
manufacturing, which accounts for about 18 percent of U.S.
business output. It grew at just 0.7 percent rate, the worst in
nearly four years, after averaging 4.6 percent in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
For all non-farm businesses, hours worked grew faster in the
first quarter than in the fourth, a 4.8 percent rate vs. a 3.5
percent rate, reflecting strong hiring.
</P>
<P>
Output growth improved too, but not as much: a 6 percent rate
in the first quarter versus a 4.9 percent rate in the fourth. As a
result, productivity growth decelerated.
</P>
<P>
In another separate report released here today, the Commerce
Department said new orders to American factories rose 1.2 percent
in April. It was the biggest increase in five months and followed
a much more modest 0.2 percent rise in March.
</P>
<P>
However, the overall rise overstated the strength in manufacturing
because it was concentrated in new orders for aircraft, a highly
volatile category. Excluding transportation, factory orders were
up a much more modest 0.3 percent in April, little changed from a
0.4 percent advance in March.
</P>
<P>
Separately today, the Labor Department said the number of
Americans filing claims for unemployment benefits surged
unexpectedly last week to the highest level in nearly five months.
</P>
<P>
Applications jumped by 30,000 to a seasonally adjusted 339,000,
the most since the week ended on January 10. Without seasonal
adjustment, actual claims fell by 8,811 to 249,640.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
