<HEADLINE> Kaunda to Quit Party Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Former Zambian president Kenneth
Kaunda announced here Thursday he will quit party politics so
that he can serve the nation and the continent on a wider scope.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda said he will step down from active politics at the next
extra-ordinary national congress of his United National
Independence Party (UNIP).
</P>
<P>
"I am strongly considering the possibility of detaching myself
from party politics so that I may make my contribution to the
nation on a wider scope," he said.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of his resignation is to serve the nation and the
continent on a wide scope and above partisan politics, said
Kaunda, who had been the country's president since its
independence in 1964 until 1991, when he was defeated by current
President Frederick Chiluba in general elections.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda said he would put up a spirited fight against many
issues dogging the continent today such as poverty, civil strife,
aids and democracy.
</P>
<P>
The former president admitted that he had made a mistake by
coming back to party politics, saying he would have been more
useful to Zambia and the continent if he had served and shared
his experiences on a neutral stand with people from all walks of
life.
</P>
<P>
He criticized some UNIP leaders for having divided the party
through squabbling among themselves over what he described as
trivial and personal issues.
</P>
<P>
He directed the party's central committee to quickly hold the
extraordinary national congress.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda said he will relinquish his party presidency at the
congress so that a new leadership could take over and save the
party from going into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
He made the announcement four days after his release from
under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, 74, was detained on December 25 last year for alleged
involvement in last October 28 coup attemp.
</P>
<P>
Six days after his arrest, he was put under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
In February this year, he was formally charged with misprision
of treason.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda was set free on Monday when a Lusaka High Court judge
said the court forgave him.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government has been urging Kaunda not to be
involved in party politics but to follow former Tanzanian
President Julius Nyerere's example so that he can be respected as
father of the nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
