<HEADLINE> Fierce Fighting Erupts in Northern Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Fierce fighting has erupted in the
north of Sri Lanka between government troops and Tamil rebels
Thursday, leaving hundreds injured on both sides, informed sources
here said.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the battles began just south of paranthan
Thursday morning and continued unabated late into the evening.
</P>
<P>
The fighting appears to be the result of a rebel counter attack
in response to a two-pronged advance on the rebel stronghold of
Mankulam town by the troops of operation Jaya Sikuru (Certain
Victory), the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Heavy casualties have been reported on both sides. Most of the
troops casualties are as a result of heavy mortar fire directed by
the rebels. But there is still no official confirmation, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The government troops are making every effort to keep up the
advance in the face of heavy mortar artillery fire, Said the
sources, adding that the Tamil rebels communications monitored by
the military indicate that the rebel commanders are making
desperate appeals for reinforcement.
</P>
<P>
The fierce fighting took place after the troops resumed their
advance last Wednesday to recapture the strategic Mankulam town on
its way to clear a 75-km supply route between the south and the
north launched in May last year.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels have been fighting a war for a separate state
in the north and east of the country since 1983. Over 55,000
people have been reportedly killed in the war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
