<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Delays Visit to Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin has
decided to postpone his visit to Ukraine scheduled for late June,
but will go ahead with a tour of some Russian regions, a senior
official announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Putin, first deputy director of the presidential
office, told a news briefing that Yeltsin's decision was prompted
by the situation on the financial markets and in the transport
sector, as well as the need for the government to take some
austerity measure to cope with the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Putin said the president's visit to Ukraine for an informal
meeting with Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma was scheduled for
June 20, but Yeltsin preferred involvement in internal problems as
against international questions.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin sent a message to his Ukrainian counterpart, proposing
that the meeting be in July.
</P>
<P>
Russia and Ukraine have been at odds for years over the
division of the Soviet-era Black Sea Fleet and the status of
Ukraine's Crimean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Though the two countries signed a friendship treaty last year,
Russia's parliament has repeatedly postponed ratification of the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's proposed internal tour includes Vologda, Novgorod and
the Kostroma regions, all located to the north and northwest of
Moscow, Putin said.
</P>
<P>
The president is expected to finally determine early next week
which of the regions he will visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
