<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sees Highest Vehicle Sales Since 1986 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The auto industry of the United
States reported that May was the best month for car and truck
sales since September 1986, the New York Times Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper reported that sales totaled 1,511,661 cars and
trucks, a 12.1 percent increase from the corresponding period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, fueled by hefty price cuts, the seasonally adjusted
annual selling rate for light vehicles reached 16.3 million cars
and trucks last month, the highest level since October 1987.
</P>
<P>
Sales of both cars and trucks increased though truck sales
showed a higher rise, it said.
</P>
<P>
Car sales totaled 793,066 units, up 6.9 percent; light-truck
sales topped 718,575 units, up 18.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Sales were popped up also by attractive incentive programs.
Auto makers spent as much as 1,600 U.S. dollars a vehicle on
incentives in May, up from about 1,100 U.S. dollars a year ago,
analysts said. In mid-April, G.M. sent certificates worth 500 to
1,000 U.S. dollars to previous buyers of G.M. products to purchase
50 different models, above and beyond other cash rebate and
low-interest loan incentives.
</P>
<P>
General Motors said today that it sold 484,168 cars and trucks
in May, an increase of 12.4 percent over May 1997. G.M.'s truck
sales increased 19.2 percent, to 226,114 vehicles. G.M.'s car
sales also increased, up 7 percent at 258,054 units.
</P>
<P>
Ford reported today that it sold 353,270 cars and trucks in
May, up 1.2 percent from May 1997. Car sales totaled 141,558, down
5.5 percent; truck sales were 211,712, up 6.2 percent from last
year. Chrysler said Tuesday that it had its best month ever in
May, selling 250,031 cars and trucks, a 27 percent jump.
</P>
<P>
Japanese and German car makers also reported strong sales in
the U.S. in May.  
</P>
</TEXT>
