<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain's Famous Cattle Market Closes down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Banbury market, one of Britain's
most famous cattle markets, closed on Thursday due to lack of
trading caused by mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
Banbury market in Oxfordshire, northwest of London, is one of
Britain's oldest with a history stretching back as early as 11th
century.
</P>
<P>
Once the biggest in Britain, the market has occupied its
current site since the mid-1920s.
</P>
<P>
The international ban on British beef exports, imposed in March
1996 because of mad cow disease, was the main reason behind the
closure of the market.
</P>
<P>
Jim Watson, chairman of the Midland Marts in Banbury, said the
cattle market was losing between 5,000 and 10,000 pounds (16,300
U.S. dollars) a week.
</P>
<P>
Other British livestock markets were heading for closure as
more farmers switched to crops from cattle because of falling beef
prices, he added.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 people will lose their jobs and the decision to
close has been partly blamed on delays in getting government
authorization for a new market.
</P>
<P>
Incomes fell along with a regional decline in cattle numbers
and livestock prices. Some livestock farmers had also been rushing
into producer clubs, which supply the best quality cattle directly
to supermarkets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mealie Meal Prices Set to Rise in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Millers Association of Zimbabwe
and the Small Scale Millers Association said Thursday mealie meal
prices will rise by between 15 and 18 percent due to the recent
hike in the prices of maize from the state-owned Grain Marketing
Board (GMB).
</P>
<P>
"In order to avoid losses and food shortages, our members will
have no alternative but to increase maize meal prices," the two
associations said in a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
In January this year, following violent food riots, the
millers agreed to hold back maize meal price increases until the
1998 crop was in.
</P>
<P>
However, the maize producer price doubled from 1,200
Zimbabwean Dollars (66.6 U.S. Dollars) to 2,400 Zimbabwean
Dollars (133.2 U.S. Dollars) per ton for the 1998 crop, while the
GMB selling price has now risen to 2,800 Zimbabwean Dollars
(155.5 U.S. Dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
The associations noted that alternative maize procurement
prices from other sources had also risen.
</P>
<P>
"General inflation had increased most of the inputs from
suppliers of other goods and services relating to overall
operating costs," they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
