<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Ministers Meet for OAU Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Ministers from all over Africa
gathered here Thursday for a 3-day meeting to prepare for the
forthcoming summit of the Organization of African Unity (OAU),
which will map out a blueprint for Africa to go toward the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
All the issues to be discussed at the 68th ordinary session of
the OAU council of ministers would be of crucial importance to
the destiny of Africa and Africans, said Prime Minister of
Burkina Faso Desire Ouedraogo, who declared the session open.
</P>
<P>
According to him, African countries have, since the last OAU
summit a year ago, made encouraging progress in handling crises,
democratization and economic development across the continent.
</P>
<P>
However, Ouedraogo admitted that Africa still remains backward
and beset with serious social problems concerning food, health
and education, among other things.
</P>
<P>
The Burkinabe prime minister thus called on the OAU member
states to redouble their efforts in promoting peace and security,
economic development and democracy in accordance with the
realities of various countries.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, Ouedraogo said, a number of agreements have
been reached by leaders of all member states during OAU meetings
at various levels.
</P>
<P>
Concerted efforts should be made to implement these documents
for more effective development.
</P>
<P>
In a keynote speech at the opening ceremony, OAU
Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim stressed the need to
establish a more peaceful and stable Africa for further progress.
</P>
<P>
Describing the ousting of Sierra Leone's coupists as "a major
victory to Africa in its efforts to engender democratic rule,"
Salim warned the military confrontation between Ethiopia and
Eritrea would only produce losers all over the continent.
</P>
<P>
"We need, therefore, to take more seriously our continental
mechanism for promoting peace through the prevention, management
and resolution of conflicts and to extend to it the necessary
political and financial support to enable it function
adequately," said Salim.
</P>
<P>
On the economic front, the OAU chief said, "We are encouraged
by the performance of the continent as most of our countries have
registered significant and sustained growth over the last years."
</P>
<P>
However, he also called for concerted efforts to be deployed
toward alleviating poverty and solving other serious
socio-economic problems, including basic infrastructure and
transport and communication facilities in African countries.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 of the 53 OAU member states attended the opening
session alongside delegates from international organizations,
including the United Nations and other countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
