<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Insurance Executives to Meet on Climate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Over 100 insurance executives and
financing experts worldwide will meet in Cologne, Germany on June
9 over the strong increase in claims of damage caused by climate
changes, the U.N. Environment Program (UNEP) announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The international insurance industry has suffered from a
series of "billion-Dollar" storms since 1987, leading to a jump
in claims. Thus it reduced availability of insurance coverage and
higher premiums, said the Nairobi-based UNEP in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The experts from more than 15 countries will discuss at the
two-day conference strategies to deal with the problem, and in
particular how to improve environmental reporting standards, said
the statement.
</P>
<P>
"A better understanding of environmental risks is of key
importance to insurance companies," Dr. Walter Jakobi, Managing
Director of Gerling Global Re which is one of the world's leading
reinsurance companies, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We can only tackle this issue if better and more specific
information is made available to us. That's why environmental
reporting is a crucial issue for our industry," he said. His
company is UNEP's co-sponsor of the conference.
</P>
<P>
Also high on the agenda in Cologne is follow-up to last year's
U.N. climate change meeting in Kyoto, Japan.
</P>
<P>
A "Corporate Global Warming Indicator" will be launched at the
conference as a tool for all companies across all sectors on how
to measure their contribution to global warming.
</P>
<P>
The indicator will allow investors to identify impacts of the
Kyoto Protocol on the financial performance of companies.
</P>
<P>
"The insurance industry has become a powerful and credible
lobby to push the environmental agenda forward," said UNEP chief
Klaus Topfer in the statement.
</P>
<P>
"Governments need to recognize that insurance companies have
much to offer when it comes to providing technical expertise and
financial resources in support of their sustainable development
policies," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There are many voices on the environmental side that continue
to say that business remains an obstacle to progress," Topfer
added.
</P>
<P>
"Instead of confrontation, we need to build partnerships, like
the one UNEP has with the insurance sector, and find solutions
together," he noted.
</P>
<P>
UNEP's alliance with the insurance industry was launched in
1995 when the first insurance companies signed on to the "UNEP
Statement of Environmental Commitment by the Insurance Industry."
</P>
<P>
Currently, more than 70 insurance firms from 25 countries have
signed the statement and have committed themselves to
incorporating environmental considerations into their operations.
</P>
