<HEADLINE> Canada Subsidizes U.S. Athletes for Pan-American Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Canada is subsidizing the travel of
athletes from the United States, the world's richest nation, to
attend a major international sporting event in the country.
</P>
<P>
As host of next year's Pan-American Games, Canada is helping
pay the bills of U.S. athletes out of a 3.5-million-U.S.-dollar
fund that will be spread among all competing nations, reports said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On average, each athlete, coach and official participating in
the Games will get nearly 500 dollars for travel to Canada,
accommodation and food.
</P>
<P>
Though major sports event organizers usually provide subsidized
accommodation, this is the first time that the travel of non-Third
World athletes has been subsidized, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is expected to send 1,200 athletes, coaches and
supporting staff to the event, which will be held in Manitoba
provincial capital of Winnipeg from July 24 to August 8 next year.
</P>
<P>
The Games, which will attract 8,500 athletes, coaches and
official from 42 countries, are overwhelmingly funded by Canadian
taxpayers, with 76 million dollars from the federal, provincial
and municipal governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
