<HEADLINE> Officials Claim Testosterone in De Bruin's Urine Sample </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Traces of artificially-produced
testosterone have been found in the urine of Michelle de Bruin,
the triple Olympic swimming champion, sports officials said on
Thursday at Seville, Spain.
</P>
<P>
The world swimming ruling body FINA announced last month that
evidence of tampering was showed in both samples of a random urine
test on De Bruin
</P>
<P>
A laboratory in Barcelona used a new test to look for
artificial evidence of the banned hormone, which is also produced
naturally in the body, after the Irish swimmer provided a urine
sample in January, said International Olympic Committee medical
chief Prince Alexandre de Merode.
</P>
<P>
De Merode refused to offer the result of the analysis but two
sport officials confirmed independently that traces of artificial
testosterone had been found in De Bruin's sample.
</P>
<P>
"That is correct. The lab did find that," one said. "But there
has been no big noise made about it."
</P>
<P>
De Bruin, who has denied manipulation, could not be punished if
the result was confirmed, because the test has not been recognised
officially as a method for catching drug-taking competitors.
</P>
<P>
Manipulating a urine sample is regarded as being just a serious
offence as providing a positive test and the swimmer faces a
lengthy ban from the sport which threatens to bring a premature
end to her career. 
</P>
</TEXT>
