<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seas Protection Highlighted on World Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
will highlight in Russian capital Moscow the protection of seas
as the theme of the annual World Environment Day celebrations set
for Friday.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 countries are to commemorate World Environment
Day Friday in an effort to raise public awareness and act on
environment which is generally degrading worldwide, the
Nairobi-based U.N. Environment Program announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 Environment Day, with the theme "For Life on Earth:
Save Our Seas," honors the U.N. International Year of the Ocean.
</P>
<P>
"The theme... is an appeal to each and every one of us to
protect and focus our attention on one of our planet's most
valuable resources: the oceans," Annan said in a statement
reaching here to mark the day.
</P>
<P>
"With changing land patterns due to the pressures of an
ever-increasing population, with the development of industries,
with the massive use of agro-chemicals, the oceans have reached
the limits of their capacity to assimilate the waste generated by
human activities," he warned.
</P>
<P>
"Our self-centered approach has damaged human health,
ecosystems and economic productivity," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
"Any approach to meaningful and effective protection of the
marine environment must factor in the full complexity of modern
life -- from politics to technology, from science to the law," he
noted in his message.
</P>
<P>
Oceans comprise more than 70 percent of the Earth's surface.
Nearly two-thirds of the global population -- some 3.5 billion
people -- inhabit coastal areas and depend on coastal and marine
environments for their livehood.
</P>
<P>
Twenty years from now, this population is expected to have
reached seven billion, according to Annan's message.
</P>
<P>
UNEP chief Klaus Topfer said in a statement available Thursday
that the "World Environment Day provides a unique opportunity to
raise environmental awareness and mobilize action."
</P>
<P>
The main event to be held in Moscow Friday will culminate with
the presentation of UNEP's Global 500 Awards to 23 individuals
and organizations from 19 countries who have made outstanding
contributions to the protection of the environment.
</P>
<P>
World Environment Day, established by the U.N. General
Assembly in 1972, is a people's event with governments,
individuals and community groups organizing countless activities
to improve their environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
