<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Holland Requires Doctors to Report Euthanasia Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- From next November 1, Dutch
doctors will have to report cases of euthanasia and assisted
suicide to regional committees in Holland.
</P>
<P>
The requirement was spelled out by a letter addressed to the
Dutch lower house of parliament by Dutch Health Minister Els Borst
and Justice Minister Winnie Sorgdrager.
</P>
<P>
The ministers claim the notification procedure is designed to
boost the confidence of doctors in the legal notification system,
and to increase their willingness to report cases where they have
helped in the ending of life.
</P>
<P>
The doctors are required to report to one of the five regional
committees, each of which is manned by an ethics expert, a medical
and a legal expert.
</P>
<P>
The committees will be established to test notified cases of
euthanasia and assisted suicide to assess whether criteria of due
care and consideration have been met. These include incurable and
unbearable suffering, repeated and well-considered requests,
consultation with an independent second physician and thorough
reporting and notification to the municipal coroner.
</P>
<P>
The committees will send their opinions to the public
prosecutions office within six weeks of notification and also to
the regional health inspector's office.
</P>
<P>
The doctor concerned will also be notified of the committee's
findings.
</P>
<P>
If the doctor has acted with due care and consideration in the
opinion of the committee, the public prosecutions office will not
instigate legal proceedings unless the Dutch Association of
Prosecutors General feels there are strong grounds for doing so.
</P>
<P>
The letter also announced that a study will be conducted to
provide greater clarity of the way in which the role of nurses and
care-workers play in the treatment process in cases involving the
ending of life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Ready to Quash 2000 Computer Bug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- China is quietly wiping out
problems with time keepers in all kinds of computers so as to
insulate its fledging huge electronic information network from
major losses when entering the new century.
</P>
<P>
As time ticks by, calls for solution of the 2000 bug problem
become increasingly louder both in China and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Chinese companies have been quicker to act than the outside
world thought.
</P>
<P>
Founder, one of the largest personal computer manufacturers in
China, has already cleansed its products of the 2000 bug.
</P>
<P>
A Founder official said that the company has used four digits
instead of two to mark years in its computers since it began
production at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
He said that since most of the major Chinese PC manufacturers
are new companies that have experienced substantial growth in the
past few years, they have adopted state-of-art technology in their
products. Therefore, most of their products do not have the bugs.
</P>
<P>
Founder has assigned resources and personnel to help its users
deal with potential problems.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government is fully aware of the urgency of solving
the 2000 bug problem.
</P>
<P>
China now has more than nine million computers, including
products of almost all major manufacturers in the world.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of the Information Industry (MII) is to conclude a
nationwide investigation into the 2000 bug problem this month. It
is expected to report its findings to the State Council and
propose solutions, including setting up a national coordination
institute consisting of representatives from MII, the State
Development Planning Commission and the Chinese Academy of
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Local finance, banking, telecommunications and transport
sectors have already set up task forces and timetables for solving
the 2000 bug problem.
</P>
<P>
China Telecom will complete a survey of its telecommunications
network all over the country so as to spot potential problems
caused by the 2000 bug this month. It will upgrade or replace all
equipment found to have 2000 bugs by July 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
An official from China Telecom said that the areas potentially
affected by the 2000 bug are in the business reporting and
equipment maintenance system.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of China is to complete the upgrading of its mainframe
computers by the end of this year. It is planning to install a new
software system in all its provincial branches and most of its
local branches before 2000. It is also upgrading its application
software.
</P>
<P>
An official from the bank said that it will spend hundreds of
millions of yuan in solving the 2000 bug problem this year.
</P>
<P>
"We will give priority to solving problems that may affect the
interests of our customers. We will do everything to secure a
smooth transition of our business system into the new century," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Govt Firm on UNITA's Implementation of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government will take up
a hard-line stance to force the opposition National Union for
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) to carry out the 1994 Lusaka
Peace Accord.
</P>
<P>
Higino Carneiro, Angolan government spokesman in the joint
committee of the peace process, revealed the decision Wednesday
evening at the airport before leaving for the U.N Security
Council meeting on Angola.
</P>
<P>
If the UNITA continues to obstruct the development of the
peace process, he said, the government will take up measures
which include the closure of UNITA headquarters in Luanda and
decide whether UNITA MPs will remain in the national assembly.
</P>
<P>
A crisis appeared in the peace process due to UNITA's refusal
to hand over the four "sensitive" regions it occupied including
Bailundo and Andulo. The recent disclosure by the U.N. envoy in
Angola, Blondin Beye, that UNITA still keeps some army units made
the crisis further deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
Under Beye's plan, local government authority should be
restored in the four cities before the end of May. But UNITA has
postponed its deadline to the end of June citing lack of
security.
</P>
<P>
It is illegal for a political party to keep its own army and
continue occupying part of the country's territory, Carneiro
noted, adding he will state to the Security Council that the
Angolan government firmly refuses UNITA's plan and demands that
the Council take up relevant measures in accordance with the
current development.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman admitted that his government might suspend the
joint committee of peace process on the pretext that UNITA failed
to implement the Lusaka peace deal.
</P>
<P>
On the military front, Carneiro said, the situation is still
unstable around the country. On Wednesday the organization
doctors without frontiers were attacked in central Angola. In
the 273 UNITA-occupied regions where local authority was resumed,
at least 40 have been snatched back by the UNITA, including five
cities.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that the Security Council meeting on
Angola might come up with a resolution to impose a third batch of
sanctions on the former rebel movement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
