<HEADLINE> 13 Projects to be Funded by SAARC Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The South Asian Development Fund
(SADF) has completed the study of 13 projects in the seven member
countries of South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation
(SAARC), Nepal's official RSS news agency said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed at a three-day meeting of the governing
board of SADF, which began Thursday in Pokhara, about 200
kilometers northwest of Kathmandu, the RSS said.
</P>
<P>
The projects include the 30-megawatt Chameliya hydro-power
project in Darchula district of far-western Nepal. The other
projects are not known yet, the RSS said.
</P>
<P>
S.A. Chaudhary, chairman of SADF and managing director of
Investment Corporation of Bangladesh, told the meeting that the
development fund is a common fund of the region which specially
focuses on the identification and development of projects, and on
development of institutional and human resources.
</P>
<P>
SADF, based in Dhaka, Bangladesh, was established in June 1996
as proposed by King of Bhutan Jigme Singye Wangchuck. The
three-window fund includes SAARC fund for regional projects, SAARC
regional fund and fund for social and infrastructure development.
</P>
<P>
Members of SADF comprise chiefs of the development banks of
SAARC countries, representatives of the Foreign Ministries of
these countries and directors of the SAARC Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Those attending the meeting include representatives from
Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri
Lanka, the seven member countries of SAARC, formed in December
1985. 
</P>
</TEXT>
