<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Nino Indicators Ease Dramatically: Meteorologist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- An Australian meteorologist said
the El Nino phenomenon, blamed for poor rainfalls over the past
year, is ending and "we can hope for a few years' breather."
</P>
<P>
The indicators of El Nino, including the warming of waters in
the Pacific Ocean and changes in atmospheric pressures, have eased
dramatically in the past month, the Australian Associated Press
Thursday quoted meteorologist Robert Fawcett from the National
Climate Center as saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"It has declined to a point that we're prepared to say that
it's over," Fawcett said.
</P>
<P>
"There are prospects of above-average rainfall across much of
Australia at the moment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Parts of eastern Queensland and New South Wales (NSW) already
had experienced recently above-average rainfalls, but Victoria and
south-east NSW were still in urgent need of rain, he said.
</P>
<P>
It could not be predicted when El Nino, which strikes
irregularly and is blamed for a variety of planetary climate
changes, would return. However, "We can hope for a few years'
breather," he said.
</P>
<P>
The current El Nino was the second strongest since 1950,
following the 1982-83 event, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Tea Yield Poises for Record Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's output of tea, a key
export earner, is poised to hit a new high this year thanks to
improved weather, better husbandry and strong global prices.
</P>
<P>
"The cumulative figure (for the year to April) now stands at
113.26 million kgs, an increase of 58.29 million kgs or 106.04
percent over the previous year," according to a statement from
the Mombasa-based Africa Tea Brokers (ATB).
</P>
<P>
"The crop figure for the month of April 1998 has been
announced at 26,760,103 kgs, showing an increase of 15,840,943 kg
or 145.07 percent over the same month in 1997," ATB was quoted by
a report reaching here Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains between October and January, followed by generous
spells of sunshine in February and March, were seen behind the
jump in production.
</P>
<P>
"The generous rains now point to a bumper tea crop," said
Agriculture Minister Musalia Mudavadi earlier.
</P>
<P>
The heavy rains, blamed on the El Nino weather phenomenon,
ruined Kenya's roads and were initially seen as a threat to
production of tea and other crops. Roads from farms to markets
are still hazardous, farmers say.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture ministry officials said favorable global prices
last year, on the back of a world shortage, have encouraged
farmers to increase the area under tea. They said farmers have
also tended their crop better to improve yields.
</P>
<P>
"High earnings always inspire better crop husbandry in Kenya.
It has been noted that the quality of tea coming out is pretty
high and production is much higher than all previous
projections," a senior agriculture ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly, we are talking of a national record," ATB said,
adding that cold and often wet conditions in all tea-growing
areas have recently inhibited growth, and leaf intake was showing
a progressive decline.
</P>
<P>
But ATB and other brokers said any spells of sunshine in the
coming months would put production on course for an all-time
record.
</P>
<P>
Weather experts have spoken of a dry spell in June after
sporadic, heavy rains in May.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is one of the world's leading producers of black tea,
with a record output of 257 million kgs reached in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Brokers point out that 1998 statistics so far show a sharp
rise in production compared to the same period in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
