<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Central Bank Resumes Bond Repurchasing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China (PBOC),
China's central bank, announced today that it has resumed the
business of repurchasing bonds from the money market in a bid to
meet commercial banks' demand for capital and accelerate the
extension of loans.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the PBOC said that this is one of a series of
measures the central bank has adopted over the past few months to
ensure the fulfilment of this year's macro-economic control
objectives, which include an eight percent economic growth, a
less than three percent rise in retail prices and stable Renminbi
exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
In April 1996 the PBOC initiated the open market bond business
in a bid to improve the central bank's macro-economic control
function.
</P>
<P>
However, only a small amount of bond repurchasing business was
done due to the subsequent condition of supply exceeding demand in
the foreign exchange market. In early 1997, the repurchasing
business was actually suspended.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that on May 26, the PBOC resumed its bond
repurchasing business in a bid to manage the base money with more
flexibility and efficiency. The trade partners are 25 first-grade
dealers in the open market, including major commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Starting June 3, the PBOC has begun to publish regularly the
central bank's bond repurchasing rates and other related
information to members of the national interbank loan market.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few months, the PBOC lifted the ceiling on
commercial banks' loans, reformed the deposit reserve system and
lowered interest rates in accordance with new changes in the
economic and financial operation. These policy measures enhanced
financial institutions' ability to extend loans and helped
increase the money supply, the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
