<HEADLINE> Fighting Breaks out in S. Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Heavy clashes have renewed in
the troubled Bay region in southern Somalia since Wednesday,
between forces from the Rahanwein Resistance Army (RRA) and those
loyal to Hussein Mohamed Aidid in and outside the town of Baidoa.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Ali Aden Qalinle, official spokesman for the RRA in
Mogadishu told reporters here Thursday that the armed
confrontations were prompted by serious armed robbery and looting
carried out by Aidid's militiamen who still control the town since
September 1995.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that his forces launched the attack Wednesday on
the militia positions of Aidid in the town, and that his forces
had lost 10 of their fighters while 15 others have sustained
gunshot wounds during the fighting before returning to their
original bases outside the town.
</P>
<P>
The RRA spokesman claimed that his forces have killed 26 of
Hussein Aidid's men and wounded more than a dozen others.
</P>
<P>
Qalinle also claimed that his forces had destroyed two battle
wagons mounted with heavy machine guns and a four-wheel-drive
pick-up truck belonging to Aidid's men in the town of Baidoa.
However, there are no independent confirmations regarding the RRA
claims.
</P>
<P>
Heavy fighting still continues Thursday between the checkpoint
of the town and a former military base, 6 km south of Baidoa,
said Qalinle, adding that his forces are now determined to
continue fighting until Aidid's men pull out of the town
unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
The faction led by Aidid did not comment on the current
fighting over the control of Baidoa where the supposedly
forthcoming national reconciliation conference is due to be held
in three months time, as declared by a statement issued
collectively by Hussein Aidid and Ali Mahdi Mohamed on April 16.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, travelers reaching here in Mogadishu also speak
about the intensity of the fighting outside the town of Baidoa
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The two sides last fought in the town of Baidoa on April 1.
The RRA forces whose armed capability is weaker than the
overwhelming fire power of Hussein Aidid's men usually culminate
their operations in a hit-and-run attack which is even more
difficult for Hussein Aidid's men to control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
