<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Wheat Production Second Highest on Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The forecast for world wheat
production in 1998 is unchanged at 592 million tons, which could
be second only to the 1997 record of 610 million tons, the
International Grains Council (IGC) announced here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Due mainly to unfavorable weather, estimates have been reduced
for Russia, Brazil and Morocco. But those for China and the United
States are higher, the IGC said.
</P>
<P>
The outlook for the world wheat trade has declined since April,
largely as a result of improved production prospects in China,
very successful procurements from India's harvest and increased
uncertainties about sales to Indonesia, it added.
</P>
<P>
Global shipments are forecast at 96 million tons, compared with
a preliminary projection of 98 million to 97 million tons in
1997-1998.
</P>
<P>
Early indications are that world wheat consumption will exceed
last season's 587 million tons, to reach 599 million tons. Most of
the increase will reflect continued growth in food use.
</P>
<P>
The IGC said, the eventual volume would depend to a large
extent on the pace of economic recovery in Pacific and South Asia,
which accounts for 40 percent of total world use for all purposes.
</P>
<P>
As for world wheat stocks, the IGC believed that higher global
requirements would necessitate a small decrease in stocks, which
were expected to decline by seven million tons, to 127 million
tons, but would still be the second highest since 1993 and
1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interbank Trading Rate Rises in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The average interest on the
Shanghai-based interbank money market rose in May as a result of
short supply of funds, according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
The interest rate on interbank lending and borrowing averaged
7.63 percent in May, up from 6.92 percent in April, the
Shanghai Foreign Exchange Trading System announced today.
</P>
<P>
The two major trading varieties have durations of 20 days and
60 days, respectively. They accounted for 30.3 percent and 34.7
percent of total transactions in May, which were valued at 2.27
billion yuan. All borrowing and lending deals were made among the
head offices of the commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics also indicate that interbank trading in
spot bonds totaled 34 million yuan last month while trading in
bond repurchasement hit 5.18 billion yuan. The average interest
for bonds was 6.95 percent in May, 0.14 percentage points higher
than in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
