<HEADLINE> Pak Shelves Plan to Export Sugar to India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has dropped the idea of
undertaking by-road export of sugar to India due to the fresh
tension between the two countries after nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
India's nuclear tests followed by threats of aggression against
Pakistan soured relations between the two countries, which forced
the Pakistani government to give up the plan of by-road trade of
the commodity, sources from the Foreign Office said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the Foreign Office earlier proposed
by-road export of sugar on the request of the Commerce Ministry,
which was expected to facilitate trade of sugar to the neighboring
country.
</P>
<P>
By mid-May, about 200,000 tons of sugar had been sold abroad
through railway wagons and by sea, of which more than a half had
been dispatched to India, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
However, the export has decelerated because of mounting tension
between the two countries since India conducted its nuclear tests
on May 11 and 13, they said.
</P>
<P>
The sources also said that the private sector now is looking
for alternative markets in Afghanistan, Indonesia, Sri Lanka and
Malaysia. The target of sugar export for the current financial
year (July 1, 1997 to June 30, 1998) is 300,000 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
