<HEADLINE> Indian Minister Sees Improvement of India-China Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Indian Minister of State for
External Affairs Vasundhara Raje said Thursday that there have
been steady improvement in India-China relations in recent years.
</P>
<P>
In a written reply to the Upper House of Parliament here, she
said that exchanges at government and people-to-people levels
between the two countries have been taking place with a view to
finding a mutually-acceptable solution to all outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
These exchanges were also meant to promote mutual understanding
and build confidence, she said.
</P>
<P>
Of late the Indian government asserted that its recent nuclear
tests were mainly due to the "threat" from China and Pakistan, yet
many opposition parties and politicians in the country do not
share the government's view. They said that the past one decade
has witnessed improvement of India-China relations and that the
Sino-Indian borders have been peaceful and quiet. They have time
and again asked the government to explain its real compulsions for
the nuclear tests on May 11 and 13.
</P>
<P>
Raje said that India was committed to the development of
friendly, good-neighborly and mutually beneficial relations with
China.
