<HEADLINE> Rescue Work Continues as Crash Toll Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Rescue workers continued an overnight
Wednesday-Thursday operation in the German town of Eschede, to try
to find more survivors or bodies from Wednesday's train crash.
</P>
<P>
The latest official reports say a total of 91 people are known
to have died so far, including two injured who died in hospital
last night. The final death toll is expected to exceed 100.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of rescue workers using five heavy cranes are working
carefully at the moment to try to lift huge chunks of a collapsed
bridge from two carriages still buried under the debris.
</P>
<P>
Police said the rescue operation could still take several hours
because any shifting of the damaged structure could bring great
danger to possible survivors and the rescuers.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl has cut short of a visit to Italy
and was due to visit the accident site later Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile hundreds of people are gathering at Red Cross
stations across the country to donate blood.
</P>
<P>
The exact cause for the accident is still unclear. According to
rescue workers and railroad officials, the front engine of the
train along with two coaches behind became detached as the rest of
the train spun out of control and slammed into the road bridge
near the Eschede rail station.
</P>
<P>
The crash at Eschede, a northeastern town, was the worst rail
accident in Germany in half a century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
