<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Handicapped Woman Helps 105 Dropouts Return To School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Fang Jinmei, a handicapped woman
in Shanghai, has helped 105 poor dropouts in east China's Anhui
Province to return to school, with assistance from her husband
and other people.
</P>
<P>
Fang, who suffers from cancer and partial paralysis, has been
bedridden for the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Her care for primary school pupils in the Gudui Hui Nationality
Autonomous Township, Changfeng County, began in 1996, when she
spent several months making 100 school-bags for the students. The
couple traveled to the township by train to deliver their gifts
personally.
</P>
<P>
In April 1997, Fang launched her own "Seeking Good-Hearted
Persons" campaign, in order to find donors to finance poor
students in the township.
</P>
<P>
Her call for donations received a warm response from this
largest industrial city of the country. A dozen individuals,
including schoolmates of her daughter at Fudan University and
other institutions have joined Fang to help these students.
</P>
<P>
So far, the number of students financed by Fang's program
has reached 105, exceeding her expectation of 100. All the money
has been sent to Gudui via "Project Hope," a national scheme for
assisting students from poverty-stricken families in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The beneficiaries sent New Year's cards to her. One of the
pupils wrote, "When I grow up, I want to be a skillful doctor to
cure your painful illness, so that you can stand up again."
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from the city's "Project Hope" office,
since 1994 Shanghai residents have donated over 76 million yuan to
the project, which has resulted in the setting-up of 600 "Hope"
schools and helped over 33,000 dropouts to return to school.
</P>
</TEXT>
