<HEADLINE> Australian Central Bank Reported to Support Failing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of Australia
(RBA) was forced to intervene to support the Australian dollar
Thursday as it continued to overshoot good domestic economic
fundamentals and tunneled below 61.00 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Although the central bank itself would not confirm the buying
intervention, the foreign exchange market was awash with talk that
it had placed orders in the market at the 60.80-U.S.-cent level.
</P>
<P>
With all the traders contacted by AAP reiterating the talk, and
a number confirming the RBA's presence, the purported action only
managed to elevate the unit by a little less than half a U.S. cent
to 61.28.
</P>
<P>
A dealer from the Commonwealth Bank said he had seen the
central bank in the market this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Another foreign exchange dealer said the RBA had been buying
the Australian dollar at 60.80 U.S. cents in the broker market.
</P>
<P>
"It has caused the market to jump up to 61.25 pretty quickly,"
the dealer said.
</P>
<P>
But the move-up proved short-lived, and by the end of the
session the Australian dollar was again nudging 61 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
It finished the day at 61.10 U.S. cents, compared to 60.93 at
the start of local trading and 61.66 here late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Battered by international investors' concern over the economic
crisis in Asia and weak commodity prices, the Australian dollar
has fallen more than one U.S. cent since the start of the week.
</P>
<P>
ABN Amro treasury strategist Peter Clay said that over the next
few days the risk remains on the downside.
</P>
<P>
"Asia continues to put pressure on the currency, commodity
prices, interest rate differentials, sentiment, it all adds up to
further pressure on the downside," Clay said.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the battered local unit was trading at
84.45 from 84.90 against the Japanese yen and at 1.0792 from
1.0947 against the German mark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
