<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Exports Decline in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's exports notched 674
million U.S. Dollars in 1997, a 14 percent fall from the 786
million U.S. Dollars recorded in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Maize exports dropped from 79 million kg to 20 million kg and
fish exports fell by half down to 17 million U.S. Dollars due to
a European Union (EU) ban, a report issued by the Uganda Export
Promotion Board (UEPB0 shows.
</P>
<P>
The fall in international coffee prices from 1.56 U.S. Dollars
per kg in 1995/96 to 1.40 U.S. Dollars in 1996/97 also caused a
drop in coffee receipts despite a high record of coffee volumes
of 4.2 million bags exported in 1996/97.
</P>
<P>
A combination of the prolonged drought and the El-Nino
torrential rains are mainly blamed for the sharp drop of
production and marketing of produce for both domestic consumption
and export.
</P>
<P>
The worst hit were beans, maize, soybean, sesame seeds, and
groundnuts.
</P>
<P>
The EU is still the major outlet of Uganda's exports,
accounting for 33 percent, followed by COMESA (27 percent), the
rest of Africa (17 percent), Far East (3 percent) and the rest of
the world (20 percent).
</P>
<P>
Regional markets, UEPB said, are becoming increasingly
important to Uganda's products, especially such low-value food
crops as maize, beans, bananas and milk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0141 </DOCNO>
