<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Launch Advanced Solar Telescope around 2003 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese scientist said here today
that China plans to send a solar telescope developed jointly by
Chinese and German scientists into space around 2003.
</P>
<P>
The space solar telescope will be the most advanced one in the
world, said Ai Guoxiang, head of the Beijing Observatory under the
Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) and an academician of CAS.
</P>
<P>
He said the telescope will consist of six major components and
weigh two tons, with its three dimensions measuring five, five and
two meters. Designed to work in space for three years, it will
help with researches on solar magnetic field.
</P>
<P>
As a chief scientist in charge of the project, Ai Guoxiang said
that total investment for the project is 500 million yuan (about
60.2 million US dollars), 80 percent of which is to be funded by
China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists will be responsible for developing the main
optical telescope with a calibre of one meter and two other
components.
</P>
<P>
Most of the current space solar telescopes launched by other
countries have calibres of only a dozen centimeters, the scientist
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is of great significance to study the impact of
solar activity on earth disasters and human telecommunications
facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
