<HEADLINE> Nigeria Wants Two-Way Communications With US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has said it will not accept
a proposed visit by high-level U.S. officials because Washington
has been sending envoys to Nigeria while banning Nigerian
officials from visiting the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at the Lagos airport Wednesday, Foreign
Minister Tom Ikimi said that the U.S. should lift its sanctions
against Nigeria so that the two countries can interact.
</P>
<P>
According to Ikimi, U.S. President Bill Clinton has sent many
envoys to Nigeria, such as Reverend Jackson and former president
Jimmy Carter, but until now, Nigeria is still "awaiting responses
from the U.S. government so that discussions and decisions could
be reached on how to remove all restrictions and sanctions
between the countries."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. should remove its sanctions, the Nigerian foreign
minister said, "so when Clinton sends his envoys here, after they
have discussed, our own Head of State can also send his own
envoys."
</P>
<P>
Ikimi said that the Nigeria has forwarded a list of
delegations to visit the U.S, but is still waiting for response
from the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. imposed sanctions on Nigeria after the execution of
Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other minority activists by the Nigerian
government on convictions of murder.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions imposed by the U.S. government include the
banning of arms sales and military exchanges and non-issue of
visas to top Nigerian government officials.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said the U.S. government, through its embassy in
Nigeria, has requested to send a high-level delegation for
discussions on Nigeria's transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
But Ikimi said the request will not be "considered and
processed" unless there is a response from the U.S. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
