<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Establishes Int'l Panel on Rwanda Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African
Unity (OAU) has announced the establishment of an international
panel of eminent personalities to investigate the 1994 genocide
in Rwanda and the surrounding events.
</P>
<P>
According to a press statement issued here Wednesday by the
OAU, the chairman of the panel is Ketumile Masire, former
President of the Republic of Botswana.
</P>
<P>
Six other members of the team are former Head of State of Mali
General Amadou Toumani Toure, Judge Mohamed Bedjaoui of Algeria,
Mrs. Ellen Johnson Sirleaf of Liberia, Ms. Lisbet Palme of
Sweden, Justice Begwati of India and Ambassador Steven Lewis of
Canada.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the panel followed the proposal made by
the Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi in November 1997 to the
seventh ordinary session of the central organ of the OAU
mechanism for conflict prevention, management and resolution at
ministerial level.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was endorsed by the central organ and also
subsequently by the sixty-seventh ordinary session of the OAU
Council of Ministers which met in Addis Ababa in February, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The OAU statement said in announcing the composition of the
panel, Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim indicated that the
investigation would address, among other things, issues such as
the root causes of the genocide in Rwanda, the circumstances in
which that genocide took place and its consequences in Rwanda and
the Great Lakes region, including the roles of states and
non-state actors before, during and after the genocide.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general also announced the establishment of a
special trust fund to support the work of the panel and ensure
its independence.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, he appealed to OAU member states and the rest
of the international community to contribute generously to the
special trust fund, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The panel which if to be inaugurated in September 1998, is to
have its secretariat in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, according to the
statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
