<HEADLINE> Commemorative Gold Coin to Be Issued for HK New Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Monetary Authority
(HKMA) announced Thursday that it will issue a Commemorate Gold
Coin to mark the opening of the new Hong Kong International
Airport at Chek Lap Kok on behalf of the Government of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
An HKMA spokesman said Thursday that the gold coin features a
design symbolizing Hong Kong's ascent into the new century, and
bears the standard Bauhinia design on the other side. The Gold
Coin is legal tender with a 1,000 HK dollar (128 U.S. dollar) face
value, he added.
</P>
<P>
It is produced by the Royal Mint of Britain in 22-carat gold
and each coin is issued with an individually numbered Certificate
of Authenticity, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"The Gold Coin will be of great commemorative value. The
mintage will be limited to 15,000 pieces worldwide, of which only
8,000 pieces are available for local distribution," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Gold Coin will be sold in Hong Kong for 3,288 HK dollars
(about 421 U.S. dollars) each and each Hong Kong Identity Card
holder can apply for one Gold Coin only.
</P>
<P>
Successful applicants will be able to collect their coins
starting from July 6, 1998, the day when the new airport is
scheduled to be put into operation.
</P>
<P>
Proceeds from the sale of the gold coins after deducting the
cost of issue will be used to fund selected charities and
community projects for the benefit of the community, the spokesman
 said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
