<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Sees General Improvement In Environment Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- China's prosperous coastal city
Shenzhen spent 2.08 billion yuan (about 260 million US dollars) on
environmental protection last year, a concrete step to fulfill its
commitment to sustainable economic development.
</P>
<P>
With the investment, the city, China's first of the five
special economic zones, has completed a series projects for waste
water and solid wastes treatment, which enables the city to have
25.1 percent of its waste water treated, up by 8.38 percent over
1996.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 98.4 percent of industrial waste water can meet the
state discharge standards, according to an environmental report
released here today by the local environmental protection bureau.
</P>
<P>
Noise pollution in the city proper and traffic arteries have
been reduced by 3.08 decibel and 1.9 decibel, respectively, while
the coverage of green areas has reached 44 percent, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The city has also increased its law enforcement efforts. Last
year, it suspended production of 11 polluting enterprises and
imposed penalties on 443 enterprises and private businesses that
violated environmental protection laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
The report noted, however, some rivers in Shenzhen are heavily
polluted and soil erosion is becoming more serious.  
</P>
</TEXT>
