<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Nordic States May Host Rwanda Genocide Convicts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Three European countries
have expressed willingness to accommodate convicts of the
International Criminal Tribunal of Rwanda (ICTR), media reports
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Denmark, Norway and Sweden, have agreed in principle to host
convicts of the tribunal, ICTR President Judge Laity Kama said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
African countries are reluctant to host the convicts because
few of their prisons match with international standards, Judge
Kama told reporters in Dar es Salaam Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Judge Kama said that ICTR convicts will only be jailed in
prisons which meet United Nations standards.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal is aware that it is inconceivable to ask African
countries to allocate funds to build prisons with international
standards because of their tight budgets. Many of them could not
even construct adequate schools and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Judge Kama said the tribunal is also negotiating with donor
countries to help any African state that agrees to host the
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four people are currently held by the tribunal. Another
11 have been indicted by the court, but are still in exile or
being held by third countries awaiting extradition.
</P>
<P>
Judge Kama and other ICTR officials arrived in Dar es Salaam
Wednesday and paid a courtesy call on President B. Mkapa. Judge
Kama presented to the president a report on the achievements of
the tribunal since its establishment in 1994.
</P>
<P>
ICTR, based in northern Tanzania's farming town of Arusha, was
established by the United Nations to try the chief suspects of
Rwanda's 1994 genocide.
</P>
<P>
Over 500,000 Tutsis and moderate Hutus were killed by Hutu
extremists in a three-month slaughter which ended with the
Tutsi-dominated Rwanda Patriotic Front seizing power.
</P>
<P>
Two cases have been completed by the tribunal. The first one
is that of Paul Akayesu, a former mayor, and the second is former
Rwanda Prime Minister Jean Kambanda who on May 1 pleaded guilty
to six counts of crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
