<HEADLINE> French Minister Voices Support to Air France Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The French Minister of Industry,
Finance and Economy Dominique Strauss-Kahn said on Thursday that
the chairman and chief executive officer of Air France Jean-Cyril
Spinetta has the entire support from the government.
</P>
<P>
He also called on Air France to continue talks with the
striking pilots "under the best conditions" while reaffirming his
support to the air company's readjustment programs.
</P>
<P>
The pilots are on the fourth day of strike on Thursday in a
dispute with the air company's plan to reduce their salaries by 15
percent in exchange for its shares. They also want the scrapping
of a double system in pays between older and younger pilots.
</P>
<P>
Air France said that like Wednesday, 83 percent of the
long-haul flights from Paris will be cancelled on Thursday, while
from 60 to 70 percent of short and medium-haul planes will remain
stranded.
</P>
<P>
The unions of pilots and the management will continue talks in
an effort to put an end to the strike.
</P>
<P>
The company's management estimated that the strike is costing
Air France 100 million francs (16.7 million U.S. dollars) each day.
</P>
<P>
The strike, which was staged 10 days from the opening of the
Football World Cup finals, is widely criticized by nearly all
French political leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
