<HEADLINE> China's Prices Remain Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- China's prices have been fairly
stable in the first four months of 1998, with consumer price index
standing at 101.2 during the period, taking the price index for
the same period in 1997 as 100, according to the latest figures
from the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai and Kunming led China's 36 major cities in consumer
price index rises -- reaching 104.2 and 104.1, respectively,
according to the statistics.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the retail price index of Fuzhou, capital of east
China's Fujian Province, rose to 101.9.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also indicate that the country's urban consumer
price index in the first four months was higher than that of the
rural areas, with the former standing at 100.6 and the latter at
99.7. 
</P>
