<HEADLINE> Mauritius-Based Firm to Set Up Warehouse in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- A Mauritius-based firm will spend
five million U.S. Dollars on setting up a warehouse in Zambia,
Zambia Daily Mail reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Director Vyash Purmessur of Sky Dream as
saying here Wednesday that his company is interested in
increasing trade with Zambia.
</P>
<P>
"We expect to make some good returns here and strengthen the
business relations with the local traders," Purmessur said. "This
is the realization that the current business climate is fine for
our type of business."
</P>
<P>
Purmessur expressed his hope that with the establishment of
the warehouse, the distribution network with the local market
will be made easier and less costly.
</P>
<P>
He said the initial forecast shows that the existence of
immense business potential especially for the supply of products
such as air conditioners and kitchen utensils.
</P>
<P>
"More trade with African countries, especially Zambia, is also
likely to improve our turnover which is now approximately 160
million U.S. Dollars a year," he said.
</P>
<P>
Free market economic framework, particularly the free exchange
rate system in place will help to stimulate regional business
activities and open up our opportunities, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This helps to create more investment and a spirit of
competitiveness in the economy for the benefit of the players and
the consumers at large," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sky Dream which has already exported a sizable volume of its
products to Zimbabwe, South Africa and Madagascar is a
jointly-owned entity with a Chinese partnership.
</P>
<P>
It has six subsidiaries dealing in construction, tourism
promotion and the supply for hard ward products. 
