<HEADLINE> Zambia Warns Foreign Investors Not to Be Racists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Racist and abusive investors in
Zambia will have their licenses withdrawn, Zambian Tourism
Minister Katele Kalumba has warned.
</P>
<P>
Kalumba sounded the warning when he toured Lufupa Safari Camp
in Eastern Province recently where some workers complained of
severe hunger and racial remarks by the proprietor, Yusuf Patel,
an Indian, according to Zambia Daily Mail.
</P>
<P>
The workers, who get 35,000 Kwacha (less than 20 U.S. Dollars)
a month, told the minister that Patel has not paid them in seven
months and that he calls them "male baboons".
</P>
<P>
They said that when they complain about how meager their
salaries are, Patel tells them to quit, but when they try to go,
he threatens them verbally by using racist remarks.
</P>
<P>
Kalumba said, "We need serious and considerate investors who
will not abuse the Zambian hospitality, financially or verbally."
</P>
<P>
Last week, a British national was deported by Zambia for
hurling racist insults at bar-men and using derogatory remarks
about Zambian President Frederick Chiluba's portrait in a
restaurant in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, tour operators in the Eastern Province complained
to Kalumba that poor government advertizing of tourist
attractions and bad roads have dogged their business. 
</P>
