<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4,000 Ethiopians Return from Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Over 4,000 Ethiopian refugees
have returned home from Sudan over the past six months, the
Ethiopian News Agency reported here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Mengesha Jatu, representative of the North
Gondar refugee affairs of the Organization for Relief and
Development in Amhara region, as saying that these refugees have
been reintegrated with their respective communities in Amhara,
Tigray and Oromia regions.
</P>
<P>
The repatriation was made possible following the agreement
between Ethiopia and Sudan through the mediation of the United
Nations High Commission for Refugees (UNHCR), said the report.
</P>
<P>
War and famine during the past three decades forced Ethiopian
refugees to stream across the border to Sudan. Since 1991, the
number of Ethiopian refugees who returned from various asylum
countries has exceeded 900,000.
</P>
<P>
According to the UNHCR, there are still some 14,000 Ethiopians
living in different refugee camps and towns in Sudan. By the end
of 1997, 38,857 of the projected 50,000 Ethiopian refugees had
voluntarily returned from Sudan since the operation resumed in
December 1995.
</P>
<P>
Another 1,189 Ethiopian refugees have been repatriated as of
mid-April 1998, bringing the total to 40,046. 
</P>
</TEXT>
