<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada Denies Behind Move to Overturn Imelda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Manila, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Philippine president-elect Joseph
Estrada Thursday denounced speculations that he could have had a
hand in the move by the solicitor general to ask the Supreme Court
to overturn an earlier conviction on former first lady Imelda
Marcos.
</P>
<P>
Solicitor General Romeo dela Cruz was reportedly planning to
file a motion to the Supreme Court to overturn its earlier
decision sentencing the former first lady on graft charges filed
against her.
</P>
<P>
"I do not know anything about that," said Estrada, belying
speculations that the move may have been the quid pro quo
arrangement reached for her early withdrawal in the presidential
race.
</P>
<P>
Imelda, who had filed her certificate of candidacy for the
presidency in the May 11 elections, withdrew from the race just
days before the polls opened and asked her supporters to cast
their votes instead for Estrada.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said he could not have ordered anyone to intercede for
Imelda, saying he has not even named an appointee to the Office of
Solicitor General.
</P>
<P>
However, Estrada had earlier been quoted as saying that dela
Cruz was among the officials of the outgoing Ramos government who
was being considered to stay on.
</P>
<P>
Cuevas Serafin, who served as justice in the Supreme Court,
recalled that normally, the High Tribunal gives weight to a motion
filed by the solicitor general, should he intercede in a case
already decided by the body.
</P>
<P>
"In cases like this, the Supreme Court ordinarily approves,"
Cuevas said, although he recalled on a specific case in the High
Tribunal during his time, when the justices reviewed the merits of
the case and decided against the solicitor general. 
</P>
</TEXT>
