<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Launches Voluntary Poverty-Relief Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province, one
of the country's most developed provinces, today launched a
poverty-relief program participated in by young volunteers.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, 20 young volunteers will set out for
northwest China's under-developed Shaanxi Province in August to
aid the local anti-poverty effort.
</P>
<P>
The program is part of a national endeavor to invigorate China
through science and education, and to eradicate absolute poverty
by the end of this century. The volunteers will work in the fields
of education, science, medical care and culture in poverty-ridden
areas for one to two years.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu will select 20 volunteers in the next two months
and train them before they leave for Yan'an and Xianyang in
Shaanxi in August. Yan'an was one of China's most important
revolutionary bases. The volunteers will work in the two places
for one year, and then be replaced by another group.
</P>
<P>
The local Jiangsu Lukui Group Company donated 200,000 yuan
(about 20,000 US dollars) in support of the program at a ceremony
this afternoon to mark its official launching. 
</P>
</TEXT>
