<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Shift Health Focus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has decided
to shift its health focus from curative treatment of diseases to
preventive health services.
</P>
<P>
State Minister for Health Phillip Byaruhanga was quoted by New
Vision daily as saying that the government has introduced a state
minister for primary health care to cater for the new priority.
</P>
<P>
He said: "since independence the budget has been tilted toward
curative services. We must tilt the balance toward primary health
care."
</P>
<P>
The introduction of the primary health care can help reduce
Uganda's unacceptably high mortality rates, HIV infection and
fertility rates, adolescent pregnancies and stunted growth, he
added.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the successful implementation of the program, a work
plan has been drawn up.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is in acute shortage of doctors. It has about one
doctor for every 25,000 people, compared to one to 1,800 in
developed countries.
</P>
<P>
However, some doctors in this east African country are jobless
due to the civil service ban on recruitment.
</P>
<P>
An official of the medical association said, "we cannot afford
to have qualified medical workers redundant. Even if the tax
revenue remains low, it is no excuse to forgo the basic medical
services."
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to exempt doctors from the ban and
called on parliament to join in the struggle to repeal
unpalatable laws which stand in the way of provision of health
services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
