<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Arms Race to Get Out of Control: Iranian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The nuclear arms race could be "out
of control" because India and Pakistan would not yield or even
bend under international pressure, said Iranian Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharazi here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The race shifts into high-gear and tends to get out of
control," Kharazi told a session of the 61-nation Conference on
Disarmament (CD). "Tension is bound to escalate."
</P>
<P>
"We must act first to freeze things where they stand and then
to initiate a reversal," said Kharazi, who visited Pakistan and
India respectively early this week.
</P>
<P>
He said that his impression was that "removing restrictions on
peaceful nuclear material might be a key toward accession to" the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) by India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister will go to New York to talk with
United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan later.
</P>
<P>
Saying that Iran has no intention to mediate, Kharazi said
that he will have further exchanges with India and Pakistan
following his discussions with Annan and some foreign ministers
present in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
