<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Libya will sign a package of agreements here
Thursday during the ongoing meetings of the supreme
Egyptian-Libyan joint committee to boost bilateral economic
cooperation, Egyptian daily Alam Al Yom reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreements, the two countries are to enhance
agricultural and industrial cooperation, boost bilateral trade
through the establishment of a free trade zone, and facilitate
transport and communications between them.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- An Egyptian company to promote Egyptian exports has
been established, with a capital of 27 million pounds (about 8
million U.S. dollars), the Egyptian version of the London-based
Arab daily Al Hayat reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The company will open new and exploit markets for Egyptian
industrial products in Europe, especially in east European
countries, Russia and other nations of the Commonwealth of
Independent States.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan will lay a 270-kilometer offshore pipeline with
the financing of a U.S. firm to transport gas from the Nile Delta
to its major industrial cities, the semi-official Jordan Times
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline, with a cost of 400 million U.S. dollars, will
first reach Jordan's Red Sea port city of Aqaba and then go on to
Amman and Zarqa to feed the thermal power plants and other heavy
industries there.
</P>
<P>
The project can reduce Jordan's electricity generation cost,
said Vice President of the U.S. firm AMOCO Bruce Ericson Wednesday
after signing a memorandum of understanding with Jordanian
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
