<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Marginally Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
finished marginally lower in directionless trade Thursday as
investor activity wound down ahead of the long weekend.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index finished 3.6 points down at 2658.4
with some late bargain hunting lifting the local bourse off its
earlier session low of 2642.0.
</P>
<P>
"There was a little bit of buying coming in this afternoon, a
little bit of bargain hunting," one broker said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index rose 0.3 points to 4625.9, while the
all resources index slipped 7.8 points to 1077.3.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks were one of the shining sectors in a lacklustre
trading day, regaining some ground from losses earlier in the
week.
</P>
<P>
The bank index jumped 27.2 points to 5782.8 with National
Australia Bank gaining 20 cents, the Commonwealth Bank climbed
10.3 cents, Westpac rose 3.6 cents and ANZ added 9.7 cents.
</P>
<P>
In other industrials, Telstra installment receipts were six
cents higher and had the highest turnover with 7.722 million
receipts changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Qantas shares dropped four cents with 6.4 million shares
traded. Most of the volume was attributable to cross trades made
by Macquarie Equities.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, BHP slipped 13 cents after stronger
gains earlier in the week, Rio Tinto added five cents, WMC shed
eight cents and MIM added two cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was 4.7 points higher to 1128.0, while the gold
bullion spot price slipped 80 cents to 292.75 U.S. dollars per
ounce.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 253.96 million shares worth 634.09
million Australian dollars (393.13 million U.S. dollars) with
falls outnumbering rises by 616 to 408. 
</P>
</TEXT>
