<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Environmental Situation Stable: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- A report issued today by the
Beijing Municipal Environmental Protection Bureau shows that the
city's environmental standards were basically stable in 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the pollution indices of the city's
atmosphere increased slightly in 1997 over the previous
year. Pollution was more serious in downtown areas and in the winter
heating season than that in suburban areas and non-heating seasons.
</P>
<P>
Due to less precipitation, the pollution indices of some rivers
rose slightly. However, the quality of drinking water sources,
namely, the Miyun Reservoir and the Huairou Reservoir, was good.
</P>
<P>
Noise pollution was reduced, and garbage from daily life
increased by 1.7 percent in 1997 to 4.6 million tons, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 the city spent 3.94 billion yuan (about 474.7 million
US dollars) on greening, supplying gas for fuel, and treating
sewage and garbage.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 2.3 million households, accounting for 94 percent of the
total, were using gas at the end of 1997. And more households were
covered by the urban centralized heating system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
