<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Historian Calls Napoleon "Disaster of France" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- French historian Roger Caratini said
in his newest book on Napoleon Bonaparte that the rising to power
of the former French emperor was a disaster for the nation, rather
than a glory as was stated by all historians in the past.
</P>
<P>
"Why Napoleon, whose role in history of France ended by the
apocalyptic withdrawal from Russia, by the diplomatic failure at
the Conference of Vienna, by the definitive defeat in Waterloo,
can still have the admirers, if not fanatics?" questioned Caratini
in his book "Napoleon, An Impostor."
</P>
<P>
He said that the outcome of the Napoleon era was terrible --
France lost 1.8 million men because of the Napoleonic wars, its
economy was ruined, its territory was occupied by one million
soldiers from enemy countries and it lost its natural frontier.
</P>
<P>
"Occupied, supervised, indebted, France was banished by Europe
and found itself shunned by the industrial revolution of which the
primary beneficiaries were Germany and Britain," he said. Napoleon
Bonaparte ruled France from 1801 to 1815 with an iron fist at home
and endless wars of aggression abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Shipping Market Opens Wider Still </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- China has scored great progress in
the process of opening its shipping market, according to sources
at a seminar closed here recently.
</P>
<P>
China has had more than 130 ports open to outside world and 120
foreign-funded shipping firms by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The country's large potential market has attracted the
world-renowned shipping firms. Forty percent of the 2,300-plus
ships leaving domestic ports every month are currently operated by
overseas shipping firms.
</P>
<P>
China has also provided the same equal treatment for overseas
firms joining the Chinese shipping market as their domestic
counterparts. For example, it allows foreign firms to operate
domestic shipping business and charges them same unloading fees
and port-using fees.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China has used loans from the World Bank, the Asian
Development Bank (ADB) and from foreign governments since the
early 1980s to build a batch of ports at the ports of Qinhuangdao,
Tianjin, Lianyungang, Qingdao, Shanghai and Guangzhou, which have
increased the country's total handling capacity by 85 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Chinese mainland has made breakthrough concerning the
shipping across the Taiwan Straits, and the "direct shipping at an
experimental basis" was launched last year. So far, ten ships that
belong to the ten shipping firms have actually put into service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Economic Growth Hit Eight-Year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Germany's economy grew at an annual
rate of 3.8 percent in the first quarter of 1998, the strongest
expansion since the German reunification in 1990, the German
Federal Statistics Office in Wiesbaden said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics office, the strong growth was
attributable to both the continued export boom as well as a strong
upsurge in domestic capital goods investment.
</P>
<P>
Despite the Asian crisis, Germany's exports soared 13.4 percent
in the first quarter of 1998 from the same period of last year,
while capital goods investment rose 10.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The office, however, cautioned that the growth figures was
exaggerated by seasonal factors, including mild weather, extra
purchases made ahead of a rise in value-added tax (VAT) in April,
as well as the inclusion of two more working days compared with
last year.
</P>
<P>
Germany's largest commercial bank, the Deutsche Bank, also said
Thursday that the special factors for the first quarter would work
in the reverse direction in the second quarter and could lead to
"clearly weaker growth dynamic" in the following months.
</P>
<P>
For the year as a whole, Germany's economy was expected to grow
at a rate of slightly over 2.5 percent, the Deutsche Bank said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
