<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao to Cut Airport Fees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Macao is to cut the fees on using the
Macao International Airport in a bid to boost the local economy,
Macao Governor Vasco Rocha Vieira said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The governor plans to sign two instructions stipulating that
the landing fees at the Macao airport will be cut by half in the
period between eleven o'clock in the evening and seven o'clock in
the morning, and airport fees will be exempted for visitors who
stay a short period in Macao.
</P>
<P>
In addition, stamp tax for export-oriented quota textile
products will also be reduced if they are shipped via air or sea.
The rate of cuts will be one percent for those leaving for China's
inland areas and two percent for other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
Those measures were aimed at boosting Macao's competitiveness
following earlier announced measures by to improve its economy,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The governor did not say when the new measures will become
effective.
</P>
<P>
Macao has been hit by an economic slowdown since 1993. The
economic growth rate for 1996 was negative and for 1997 less than
one percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
