<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Asset Management Firm to Seek Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim announced here Thursday that the proposed
Asset Management Company (AMC) will initially source 10 billion
ringgit (about 2.551 billion U.S. dollars) from local and
international bond markets.
</P>
<P>
The AMC, to be set up within two week's time, will acquire some
of the non-performing loans (NPLs) in local financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the details of the AMC at a news conference, Anwar
who is also Finance Minister said the AMC will issue bonds valued
between 1 billion U.S. dollars and 2 billion U.S. dollars with
government guarantee.
</P>
<P>
The AMC, once in operation, must be independent, Anwar said,
adding that it would be subject to external audit.
</P>
<P>
Its establishment will allow financial institutions saddled
with NPLs to unwind them and work towards "cleaning up" their
balance sheets.
</P>
<P>
The move is expected to help spur greater business activity and
speed up the country's economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
Up to March this year, the rate of NPLs stood at 9.3 percent of
total loans in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
