<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 09:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Newspaper Publicizes Revised U.S. Pullback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 4 (Xinhua)-- An Israeli newspaper Thursday
publicized the details of the revised U.S. proposal which demands
Israel carry out a three-stage further redeployment within 12
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan published on the Hebrew daily Haaretz, 1
percent of Israeli controlled territory Area C will go to
Palestinian controlled Area A; 12 percent of Area C will go to the
jointly controlled Area B; an additional 14.2 percent of Area B
will go to Area A.
</P>
<P>
A joint Israeli-Palestinian committee will be established for
the third phase of the further redeployment, according to the plan.
</P>
<P>
The plan, presented to both Israeli and Palestinian sides last
Wednesday by U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross, demanded that the
permanent status negotiations should start when Israel begins
carrying out the pullbacks.
</P>
<P>
According to the draft, Israel should refrain from building
new settlements, limit expansion of existing settlements and land
confiscation, and stop the planned demolition of 1,800 Palestinian
homes.
</P>
<P>
For its part, the Palestine Liberation Organization's Executive
Committee should ratify the changes to the clauses in the
Palestinian Charter, which call for Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
The plan also said that Israel and the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA), as well as the U.S., would strengthen their
cooperation on security issues. Haaretz said Israel had succeeded
in inserting a clause in the draft calling for creating a
"systematic program" by the PNA to confiscate illegal weapons.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported Thursday that Ross is holding talks in
London with Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen), deputy to PNA President
Yasser Arafat, and Palestinian Legislative Council Speaker Ahmed
Qureia (Abu Ala) to discuss the revised U.S. plan. Abu Mazen is to
report the result of the talks to Arafat later Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has not said publicly
if he would accept the revised plan. But he said Wednesday that he
believed the agreement on redeployment would be approved by the
Knesset (Parliament).
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been making tremendous efforts for the past nine
months in solving the Israeli-Palestinian dispute over the size of
further Israeli redeployment in the West Bank, but achieving
little progress so far.
</P>
<P>
While denying the U.S. had given Israel a deadline to accept
its proposal, U.S. Ambassador to Israel Edward Walker said
Wednesday the U.S. could announce the new initiative in days.
</P>
<P>
This was a clear indication that Washington is getting
increasingly impatient with the lack of progress in its mediation
and the continued deadlock in the peace process, that threatens to
spark widespread violence in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
