<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Province Developing Hi-tech Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Hi-tech industry has become an
economic growth point in central China's Hubei Province. Revenue
from hi-tech industry zones in the province amounted to 16.1
billion yuan (1.94 billion US dollars) last year, an increase of
54 percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Hubei provincial government worked out a series of
preferential policies for the growth of hi-tech industry. The
province appropriated 20 million yuan of working funds (2.4
million US dollars) for ten high-tech industry projects in 1997,
and 50 million yuan (6 million US dollars) the following year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that Hubei now has 785 hi-tech enterprises,
with 46 having sales revenue of over 100 million yuan (12 million
US dollars), five others over 500 million yuan (60 million US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
In 1997, among the top ten enterprises with reported biggest
profits, four are high-tech enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The province increased investment in such high-tech industries
like electronics information, biology technology, new medicine and
new materials, which has formed the scales to some extent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Privatize 30 Percent of Airbus Maker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- France plans to privatize 30 percent
of the state-owned Aerospatiale Group, said the Echos daily on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Some 6 billion francs (1 billion U.S. dollars) of the stocks of
the Group, the maker of Airbus planes, will be put to the market.
</P>
<P>
Recently the French government transferred 48 percent of the
stocks of the Dassault Aviation group of France to Aerospatiale.
</P>
<P>
Dassault Aviation is a private group which produces the Mirage
and Rafale war planes.
</P>
<P>
The move is expected to enable Aerospatiale to set up alliance
with other plane makers in France and Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
