<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 09:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Minister Stresses Need for Holding Arab Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority Higher
Education Minister Hanan Ashrawi Thursday reiterated the need to
hold an emergency Arab summit to come up with a firm stance
against Israel's intransigence in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Cairo-based Voice of Arabs Radio over
telephone from Gaza, Ashrawi said the current Israeli government
insists on going ahead with its policy, reneging the agreements
signed with the Palestinian side despite all initiatives and
efforts exerted to revive the peace drive.
</P>
<P>
A just and overall peace is the only way to bring about
security for all the parties concerned, she stressed.
</P>
<P>
Ashrawi said she has no confidence in achieving any progress in
the peacemaking as long as the present Israeli government remains
in office.
</P>
<P>
For several months, the Palestinians have been urging for an
Arab summit to rally support for their position in the peace
negotiations and to secure a common strategy to confront the
intransigent policies of the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest issue of Egypt's English-language Al
Ahram weekly, the Palestinians want the meeting to take a step in
the direction of the last 1996 Cairo summit that produced an
agreement that substantially slowed down the pace of normalization
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
They also expect the Arab leaders to discuss lowering their
countries' diplomatic representation in Israel and using their
economic clout to serve the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arab leaders are engaged in intensive consultations in
convening a restricted or expanded summit as the stalemate in the
Palestinian-Israeli peace-making has lingered for 15 months.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., whose latest peace initiative is resisted by Israel,
has asked the Arabs to put the summit on hold for a while as it is
pressing Israel to accept the package. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
