<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Conditions Drive Animals Out of Kruger Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The growing number of large
wild animals escaping from the Kruger National Park into farmland
in Mpumalanga Province, northeast South Africa, are causing
extensive damage to crops and posing serious health risks.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists have said that the sudden surge in animal
escapes stemmed from growing overpopulation within the park,
following a moratorium on elephant culling, and the dilapidated
condition of the southern boundary fence.
</P>
<P>
In addition, late summer rains in the park also contributed to
large animals foraging outside the park and the situation was
expected to become worse during the winter months.
</P>
<P>
Escaping animals could spread serious disease to cattle and
other domesticated animals, Ertjies Rohm of the Mpumalanga Parks
Board said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The unhindered movement of the animals poses a health risk,
with the possible spread of foot and mouth disease and bovine
tuberculosis," Rohm said.
</P>
<P>
Farmers living in the area have suffered thousands of Rand
(one U.S. Dollar equals to about five Rand) in damage after
elephants and hippos trampled on their sugarcane and citrus
crops, African Eye News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
Roughly the size of British Wales or the state of
Massachusetts of the United States, the Kruger National Park
which occupies nearly two million hectares, is 350 km long from
north to south with a maximum width of 90km. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Cuts Rice Exports in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam will cut its rice exports to
250,000 tons in June to assure food security for the country
which has been suffering from a prolonged drought, official
reports said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During the first five months, Vietnam saw its rice exports up
with 2.65 million tons shipped abroad, doubling those of the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The government still has to see how much rice will be harvested
during the summer-autumn and winter crops before deciding whether
to resume exports to the normal level, said a senior official.
</P>
</TEXT>
