<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Banks Cut Mortgage Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- All the major money banks in New

Zealand have announced cuts to their floating mortgage rates in
response
to the falling interest rates on the money market.
</P>
<P>
ASB Bank, ANZ-Postbank, Countrywide Bank, Bank of New Zealand
(BNZ),
the National Bank and the WestpackTrust Bank cut their floating
interest
rate by three quarter of a percentage point to 10.5 percent from
11.25
percent.
</P>
<P>
However, one of the banks, BNZ has warned that the lower rate
may not
last long in view of the volatile exchange rates of the Kiwi
dollar
because of fear of the Asian crisis impact.
</P>
<P>
The banks have been under pressure from politicians and the
Consumer
Institute who charged that the banks set a too high profit margin
between
their mortgage rates and the interest rates on the money market.
</P>
<P>
The banks borrow from the money market and set their lending
rates in
accordance with the 90-day bill rate, which is usually 1 to 1.5
percentage points lower than the mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
With the fall in the exchange rates of the New Zealand dollar,
the 90-
day bill rate has come down from over 9 percent one month ago to
the
present 8.5 percent. But the banks did not adjust their lending
rates
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
The banks argued that they could have lowered their mortgage
rates
last week, but the New Zealand dollar had not stabilized and the
volatility on the money market had prevented them from doing so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
