<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 8:00 GMT, June 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA -- Six people were slightly injured Wednesday night when
unidentified attackers hurled a grenade into a coffee house in
Turkey's largest city of Istanbul, the semi-official Anatolia News
Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a similar development, an explosion took place in the second
car of a commuter train Wednesday night after just leaving
Yesilkoy station in Istanbul, killing one man and injuring at
least three others, a local TV reported. (Turkey-Explosion)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Over 1,100 people died in rioting in Jakarta and
other parts of Indonesia from May 12 to 25, newspapers Thursday
quoted the National Commission on Human Rights as saying.
</P>
<P>
In a three-page statement, The commission said it "has received
 quantitative reports that there was an excessive material loss
because of the rioting, including the killings of 1,188 people and
101 injuries along with some cases of rape." (Indonesia-Riots
Toll)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The Bosnian Republica Srpska (Serb Republic) and the
Muslim-Croat Federation signed a memorandum on police cooperation
to ensure civil security on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum was signed Wednesday after talks in Banjaluka
between Milovan Stankovic, interior minister of the Republica
Srpska, and Mehamed Zelic, interior minister of the Muslim-Croat
Federation.
</P>
<P>
The police forces of the two entities will also join in the
fight against terrorism, drug trafficking, and organized crime.
(Bosnia-Police Cooperation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Members of the Organization of American States (OAS)
Wednesday urged India and Pakistan to conduct no more nuclear
tests similar to those they carried out last month.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution passed at the 28th OAS annual meeting, foreign
ministers or their representatives from the 34 member states
unanimously condemned the nuclear tests conducted by India and
Pakistan last month.
</P>
<P>
It urged India and Pakistan to sign immediately and
unconditionally the NPT and seek peaceful means to settle their
differences. (OAS-India-Pakistan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Chamber of Commerce Wednesday said the
Clinton administration's effort to extend normal trade relations
to China is the right step for business and consumers, and urged
Congress to support the president's decision.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton proposed earlier Wednesday the renewal
of China's Most-Favored Nation (MFN) trade status for another
year. He said that it is vital for the United States to maintain
normal trade relationship with that Asian country.
</P>
<P>
The MFN status allows goods to be sold in the U.S. with normal
tariffs. It is extended to most nations and was first granted to
China in 1979. The annual renewal of China's MFN has become an
opportunity to debate the U.S. China policy, a controversial issue
in the United States for years. (US-China-MFN)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain named an international commission Wednesday
which is responsible for restructuring the Northern Irish police
force under the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The commission is headed by Chris Patten, the former Hong Kong
governor, and made up of seven members. They include professors,
lawyers and crime experts from Britain, Canada and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The commission has been established under a historic accord
approved by voters last month which saw policing reforms as a key
element in reducing tension in the British
province. (UK-N.Irish-Police) 
</P>
</TEXT>
