<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Holds Talks with PNG PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
on Thursday held talks here with visiting Papua New Guinean (PNG)
Prime Minister Bill Skate, discussing bilateral and international
issues.
</P>
<P>
Briefing reporters after the talks, Skate said he held
successful and wonderful discussions with the president. They
discussed among other things the economic, cultural and defense
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, who arrived here Wednesday afternoon for a
three-day visit, expressed support for the Indonesian government
during their difficult times. He felt confident that the
Indonesian government will find a solution to their difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Skate expressed the hope that the two countries will work close
together in the future.
</P>
<P>
Skate is the first head of government to visit Indonesia since
Habibie assumed the presidency on May 21.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a state dinner hosted by Habibie on Wednesday
night, Skate said that mutual respect is vital not only to
relations between Indonesia and PNG, but to the peaceful and
mutually productive conduct of international relations generally,
including regional, inter-regional and global cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the two governments have already achieved an
impressive record of cooperation at the United Nations and other
forums.
</P>
<P>
Habibie said in his speech that trade volume between the two
countries was still too small and should be increased.
</P>
<P>
He briefed his guest on the monetary and economic turmoil
Indonesia has been experiencing since mid 1997. He said the
Indonesian government hoped that its efforts to cope with the
problems would be successful as the country received assistance
from other countries and international institutions.
</P>
<P>
Skate is scheduled to visit a state aircraft manufacturer in
Bandung, West Java, and a state ship-builder in Surabaya, East
Java.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving Indonesia, Skate will visit the industrialized
island of Batam near Singapore, as Papua New Guinea is planning to
establish an area similar to Batam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
