<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grain Producer in Northeast China Involved in Animal Husbandry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Heilongjiang Province, a leading
grain producer in northeast China, has expanded its animal
husbandry so that it accounted for 32.9 percent of the province's
1997 agricultural output value.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the provincial government decided to expand the animal
husbandry business to solve the grain oversupply and marketing
problem. Last year, animal husbandry in the province consumed 8.5
billion kg of grain, but generated 4.25 billion yuan in added
value goods, while grain output went up to 31 billion kg.
</P>
<P>
The province produced 1.93 million tons of meat, 1.95 million
tons of dairy products, 1.12 million tons of eggs in 1997, all of
them registering significant increases over the 1994 figures.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of this year, the province had a 10
percent increase in meat, egg, and milk output.
</P>
<P>
There are 603,000 households involved in livestock business
and 10,700 breeding centers in the province.
</P>
<P>
Some large companies processing livestock products and large
markets have helped the sector. As a result, the province no
longer consumes all its livestock products but also sells them
in other provinces.
</P>
<P>
About 1.5 million rural laborers are working in the production,
processing, and selling of livestock products in Heilongjiang,
accounting for a fourth of the province's rural work force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 08:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One of World's Oldest Men Dies in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 4 (Xinhua) -- A Lebanese man, who boasted that
death had "forgotten" about him, died Wednesday, at the age of 136
according to his memory, the Daily Star reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ali bin Mohammed Hussein, also known as Ali Zelem, who claimed
himself to be the oldest man in the world, had a heart attack and
passed away quietly at his home in Qinieh village in central
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
His death deprived his village of a walking history book that
stretched back to the days of the Ottoman rule, the newspaper
report said.
</P>
<P>
The man, also popular in the village for composing verses of
zajal, or traditional sung poetry in the Lebanese dialect, was
survived by 93 children, grandchildren and great grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
A great regret for Zelem was that The Guinnes Book Of Records
refused to proclaim him as the world's oldest living human being
as he was unable to provide a document to prove his age.
</P>
<P>
He argued that he had been born several decades before the
identity card system was first introduced in the new, independent
Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique: Grain Purchase to Rise in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican government has
predicted that the purchase of grain in the whole country this
year will reach 439,000 tons, 11 percent up against last year's
397,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The Director of the National Bureau of Internal Commerce, Jose
Paulo, disclosed this here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Among the purchase grain, maize will remain the number one, up
by 14 percent against last year's to reach 264,000 tons,
Thursday's Noticias newspaper quoted Paulo as saying.
</P>
<P>
The maize growing areas are mainly in central and northern
Mozambique. The purchase volumes of maize in central provinces of
Zambezia and Manica will be 60,000 tons and 50,000 tons
respectively while the northern Nampula Province will collect
60,000 tons of maize from the growers.
</P>
<P>
Cassava will rank the second with 55,000 tons getting in,
followed by beans (36,700 tons) and copra (36,500 tons), Paulo
said, adding that the purchase of rice will be some 19,000 tons
this year. Rice is one of the staples in southern Mozambique, the
capital city of Maputo in particular.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the total grain yield in Mozambique this
year will top 1.6 million tons compared with 1.5 million tons last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
