<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Last Of A Breed Of Tibetan Hunters Lays Down His Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Sixty-two-year-old Daden, who lives
in the village of Qionglin in the Tibet Autonomous Region,
recently put away his guns and bows and arrows, the last hunter of
the Lhoba people.
</P>
<P>
Pointing to his grandsons, he says, "They're all studying in
school, and it seems they'll only need pens, and not arrows."
</P>
<P>
The Lhoba, who number fewer than 3,000, are one of the smallest
of China's 55 ethnic minorities. Before Tibet's
democratic reforms in 1955, the Lhoba lived in wooden huts in the vast
forests and mainly hunted for a living.
</P>
<P>
A Lhoba man used to be armed with a bow and arrows, hunting
dogs, and three knifes to help him make his way through the bush,
kill animals, and cut the meat up.
</P>
<P>
It was Lhoba tradition to share whatever they caught among all
tribe members, with the exception of the fur, bear's gall, and
deer's musk, which had to be sold to the local government.
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes we
had to eat wild plants, when we couldn't get enough animals,"
Daden says.
</P>
<P>
In the 1960s, the Lhoba began to move to valleys and the
plains, where they had access to roads and electricity, and with
the the government's help, the ethnic group began to make bamboo
items, use charcoal, and cultivate grain. Sometimes they still
hunted because of a lack of grain.
</P>
<P>
"Now my family no longer needs me to hunt, because my children
have better ways of making money," he explains. His family of
eleven grow grain on more than one hectare of farmland and raise 30 head of
cattle, and produce more than 5,000 kg of grain every year.
</P>
<P>
Daden now also owns a truck, a bulldozer, and four saws, and
the family have got involved in forestry and construction work.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the family earned more than 50,000 yuan and become one
of the richest families in the village. In their leisure time,
Daden and his family members enjoy the programs on color TV, and
listen to music and watch films on their video equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Eyes Markets in C. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Trade Promotion Agency,
ZIMTRADE, is working to open up export markets in Congo
(Brazzaville), Gabon, the Central African Republic and the Great
Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
In its latest quarterly magazine, ZimTrader, released in
Harare Thursday, the organization said that it would carry out
market surveys in these countries to identify specific
opportunities for Zimbabwean products.
</P>
<P>
"Desk research for these markets so far indicates that there
are opportunities in pharmaceuticals, building and construction
materials, processed foods, leather goods, fresh fruits and
vegetables, corned beef and others," ZIMTRADE said.
</P>
<P>
"Local companies are advised to start looking at these
potentially lucrative markets and liaise with ZIMTRADE," it
added.
</P>
<P>
While Gabon, Congo (Brazzaville) and the Central African
Republic are small markets in terms of population with a combined
total of 5.7 million people, ZIMTRADE said, but they have high
purchasing powers.
</P>
<P>
Gabon whose major source of wealth is oil, has a per capita
income of 2,750 U.S. Dollars, and is the second richest country
in terms of per capita income in Africa after Mauritius.
</P>
<P>
Potential exports to the tiny, ethnic-conflict-prone nations
of Rwanda and Burundi include fresh, frozen and canned beef,
fresh fruits and vegetables, pork and pork products, and hardware
fixtures and fittings.
</P>
<P>
The trade promotion body said although recently rocked by
civil war, Congo (Brazzaville) would soon be calm and its economy
is financed by offshore oil fields.
</P>
<P>
"All the markets under consideration are wholly
import-dependent, giving Zimbabwe the room to develop export
relations with the importers," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
