<HEADLINE> Police Ferret out Major Cultural Relics Theft Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Police have arrested the
members of a crime gang who is accused of involvement in theft of,
trading, and trafficking in cultural relics in Handan city in
north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
The nine gang members stole three bronze horses, 209 items of
fine gold thread clothing, a bronze tripod, a pure gold
waist-plate, and other treasures that date back to the Warring
States Period (475 B.C.--221 B.C.), and which were under top
state-level protection.
</P>
<P>
The relics came from three robberies of an imperial tomb in
Handan, capital of the Zhao State, done by digging a 35-meter
shaft to the tomb last year.
</P>
<P>
The police have returned three bronze horses and another bronze
piece that was smuggled to Hong Kong and Britain last month.
</P>
<P>
The earliest piece of clothing came from an imperial tomb of
the Western Han Dynasty (206 B.C.--24 A.D.). in Hunan Province.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
