<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Beef Exports Decrease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe lost more than 11 million
U.S. Dollars in exports in the last two years by failing to meet
the European Union beef quota.
</P>
<P>
Because of this failure, the country earned 29 million U.S.
Dollars in 1996 and 23 million U.S. Dollars last year, bringing
the total earnings in the last two years to about 53 million U.S.
Dollars, the Herald daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
If it had fulfilled the obligation, Zimbabwe could have earned
over 62 million U.S. Dollars, the paper noted.
</P>
<P>
In an interview Wednesday, Chairman of the Cattle Producers
Association Les Mallett said that the shortage of slaughter stock
had came about because cattle producers were rebuilding their
herds which had dwindled significantly following recent droughts
and subsequent poor seasons.
</P>
<P>
The failure to meet the EU annual beef quota in the last two
years had not only affected foreign currency earnings but dashed
the country's hopes of having the quota increased to 13,000 tons,
he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 the country failed to fulfill the quota by 2,500 tons
while last year it failed by 1,550 tons.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has only exceeded the quota twice, in 1993 when it
exported 9,740 tons and in 1995 when it exported 11,654 tons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
