<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Civilian Diplomats" (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Foreign guests usually have a lot of questions to ask about
Chinese life, rents, the cost of electricity and water, family
incomes, and city life, and the "diplomats" patiently answer
them. Also, they teach the guests how to cook Chinese dishes and
lead them to a glimpse of their small and narrow rooms.
</P>
<P>
Several months ago, Li was visited by a Japanese family,
Mr. Kojima Takeshi, his wife Kojima Yaeko, and their two children.
</P>
<P>
Li not only offered her own bedroom to them, but took the
family on a tour of the city's scenic spots and markets, forming a
deep relationship with the visitors.
</P>
<P>
Five days passed. As they were departing, Mrs Kojima Yaeko
hugged Li and cried, because the time was so short.
</P>
<P>
Days ago, a letter from Japan arrived and Mrs Kojima Yaeko said
that she is determined to visit China again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civilian Diplomats Active in Shanghai (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- After she retired from her post at
a toy company, Li Amao, a 68-year-old Shanghai woman, never
thought that she could become a "civilian diplomat".
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, Li has played host to 10,000 tourists
from abroad who are interested in the lives of ordinary Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Li's is a typical three-member family, living in a room with
simple furniture and a large number of pictures. So it was chosen
by the neighbourhood committee for the job.
</P>
<P>
Many of the pictures are now of guests and Li. She says
happily, "I have friends all across the globe."
</P>
<P>
The community where Li lives is one of the 15 in Shanghai that
are open to foreign tourists and started inviting foreign guests
as early as in the 1950s. However, it was in recent years that a
large number of foreign tourists began visiting her community,
mostly after China's reforms and opening-up in 1978, Li explains.
</P>
<P>
Her community -- Caoyang New Village -- has 50,000 residents,
100 of whom are "civilian diplomats" who played host to 8,600
foreign tourists in 1997 alone.
</P>
<P>
In order to better communicate with foreign guests, youngsters
in the village have set up their own English Corner where they can
meet periodically to practice oral English. The old ladies,
however, organized a chorus and learned to sing songs in English,
Japanese, and French and often give joint performances with the
guests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
