<HEADLINE> Africa Hopes to Install 50M Phones by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Africa hopes to install 50 million
telephones by 2000 so as to boost the telecommunications sector
which is key to the continent's economic success, a visiting
South African minister has said here.
</P>
<P>
"Africa has only 14 million telephones, less than half of the
telephones in Europe today," South African Minister of Posts,
Telecommunications and Broadcasting Jay Naidoo said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Naidoo made the remarks following a meeting with his Kenyan
counterpart William ole Ntimama in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers resolved to work closely in the
liberalization process of the telecommunications sector.
</P>
<P>
The South African minister said that they have agreed on a
framework on how African countries would network and be financed.
</P>
<P>
Ntimama said Kenya has a lot to learn from South Africa which
started liberalization of the telecommunications sector a few
years ago.
</P>
<P>
The teledensity in Kenya is less than one percent compared
with an average of 60 percent in the West. 
</P>
</TEXT>
