<HEADLINE> Pay Team Set Up to Curb Corruption in Uganda's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- A special pay unit has been
established in the Uganda People's Defense Forces (UPDF) to curb
corruption and fraud in the army.
</P>
<P>
The team, appointed recently by President Yoweri Museveni, has
25 members who has been deployed in five army divisions
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
As a replacement of the pay-masters, the team is mainly made
up of university graduates and it is supposed to investigate
suspected fraud areas.
</P>
<P>
"The pay team was also given special powers to supervise
acquisition of supplies and procurement of goods in the force
which in the past was greatly abused," a military source was
quoted by the New Vision newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The situation has improved a lot since the team took over, the
source added.
</P>
<P>
When addressing officers and men of the UPDF at the 17th Army
Day celebrations at Bombo barracks on February 6, Museveni
decried the rampant corruption in the army.
</P>
<P>
The president said that the country has been losing some 4.8
million U.S. Dollars annually due to fraud in salaries and food
allowances in the Fourth Division alone. 
</P>
