<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reinforcing River in East China for Greater Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 4 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province is
taking steps to make the Minjiang River safer near Fuzhou, the
provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
In the past, two branches of the Minjiang took the load of
flood waters, but since the 1990s, the Beigang River's banks have
collapsed because of excessive digging for sand, while the Nangang
has silted up and has no flow.
</P>
<P>
So, the local government spent 30 million yuan to re-inforce 33
dangerous sections of dykes, and now, the first and second phases of
the project have been completed and the third phase is
underway.
</P>
<P>
And, it set up a special team to study the changes of
the river course on the lower reaches.
</P>
<P>
Digging for sand in the Beigang has now been prohibited and
clearing work on the Nangang began last May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
