<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Pest Threatens Chinese Vegetable Plots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, June 4 (Xinhua) -- A new crop killer, the vegetable
leaf miner (Liriomyza sitivie), is invading the vegetable fields
in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
This global threat has left its mark on at least 40 other
countries and regions, and in China, has spread to 24 provinces,
cities and autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural department sources in Gansu Province say that
since the province was hit last winter, 3,000 ha. of land in 25
counties have reported losses caused by the insect.
</P>
<P>
Agronomists say that the vegetable leaf miner prefers pumpkins,
cucumbers, tomatos and eggplants, and that it reproduces well
under greenhouse conditions.
</P>
<P>
Government departments are organizing teams to help farmers
combat the pest. The Yuzhong Plant Pesticide Co. Ltd has worked
out an effective chemical to use against the adult insect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
