<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jazz Edge Bulls in Overtime to Win NBA Finals Game 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- John Stockton scored seven of
Utah's nine points in overtime as Jazz edged the Chicago Bulls
88-85 in Game 1 of the NBA Finals in Salt Lake City on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Stockton, 36, who hopes to win the championship for the first
time with a career of 14 years in NBA, displayed a brilliant play,
scoring 24 points for Jazz. His final shot in the last second
sealed the tough-fight victory.
</P>
<P>
Karl Malone, who had a 10-day layoff with the team after
winning the Western Conference finals, looked rusty most of the
time when the tough guy missed 10 mid-range jumpers and was on 4
of 19 shots in the first 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
But he came back strongly in the final two minutes of the
regular time, hooking a pair of jumpers to force a 79-79 tie.
Malone contributed 21 points plus 14 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
Michael Jordan led a game high 33 points, and Scottie Pippen
added 21 for the Bulls, who came to Jazz's home-court tired after
beating the Indiana Pacers 4-3 in the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
The halftime wound up 45-40 in favor of Utah. Jordan scored 20
points in the first two quarters, but Malone only got nine.
</P>
<P>
Entering the third quarter, the Jazz led a 8-0 run to widen the
gap to 53-45 and managed to keep the lead until 2:30 left in
regular time.
</P>
<P>
Jordan shot two jumpers before Pippen scored a three-pointer to
tie 75-all.
</P>
<P>
In the overtime, the Jazz quickly ran ahead to lead 84-79,
leaving the Bulls struggling in their wake during the rest of time.
</P>
<P>
With 43 seconds left and the ball in Chicago's control, it blew
up by Luc Longley, perhaps the worst center of all the NBA teams.
He tried to force his path to the hoop but lost the ball
again. The score then stood at 82-86.
</P>
<P>
With 3.5 seconds remaining and 85-88 trailing, Pippen got a
pass but missed the tying 3-pointer at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
Stockton wrapped up the game with a 9-for-12 free shooting,
eight assists and two steals.
</P>
<P>
"They just kept coming back. We're going to have to play better
than that if we're going to win this thing," Stockton said.
</P>
<P>
"Stock's got the ice water in his veins," Russell said. "You
know he wants that ring. Stock took over that game."
</P>
<P>
The second game is slated for Friday, also in Salt Lake City.
</P>
</TEXT>
