<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Okays 500M Dollar Container Terminal Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has okayed
the 500 million U.S. dollar Chittagong port container terminal
project, a daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government had given a go-ahead to the U.S. container port
operator, Stevedoring Services of America (SSA), to set up an
international container terminal near the country's biggest port
city of Chittagong at a cost of about 500 million dollars, the
Daily Star quoted Shipping Ministry sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The project, the largest single foreign investment project in
this South Asian country and to be implemented in the form of
build-own-operate (BOO), would also have an inland container
terminal to be built near the capital city of Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
The terminal near Chittagong Port would be partially
operational in one and a half years' time, and the whole project
would be ready by the year 2001 when it could handle 600,000
containers annually, according to SSA officials.
</P>
<P>
The SSA officials hoped that it would help Chittagong Port
become a South Asian shipping hub, catering to local, regional and
international trade.
</P>
<P>
The inland container terminal would be built on the other bank
of Buriganga River at Pagla near Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
Both terminals would be fully computerized and help ease
congestion at Chittagong Port and at the same time help boost
local trade.
</P>
<P>
Congestion at Chittagong Port had reached a choking point as it
could handle about 300,000 containers annually, far above its
capacity, delaying loading and unloading.
</P>
<P>
The government had formed a project implementation committee to
help its speedy implementation. Preliminary work had already
started and work would begin in full swing from October this year,
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
