<HEADLINE> Voting Under Way in S.Korean Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 4 (Xinhua) -- South Koreans went to the polls
Thursday in a mood of apathy and indifference to vote in the
country's second local government elections.
</P>
<P>
The Central Election Management Commission was predicting the
turn-out would be less than 60 percent of the 32.53 million
eligible voters, compared to 68.4 percent in the first local
government elections in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Voters will choose a total of nine governors, seven big city
mayors, 232 heads of small cities and counties, and 4,180
councillors during polling from 6 a.m. to 6 p.m..
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Commission Chairman Choi Jong-young urged the
public to vote at the 16,161 balloting stations across the country
and candidates made a last ditch bid for votes by conducting
street campaigns late into the evening.
</P>
<P>
Election observers said the lack of voter interest could be
blamed on the effects of the continuing economic crisis caused by
corporate collapses and bad loans by financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Regional political differences are expected to be highlighted
in the elections with candidates of the ruling coalition of the
National Congress for New Politics and the United Liberal
Democrats reportedly tightening their political stronghold on
Cholla and Chungchong provinces. Those from the major opposition
Grand National Party are ahead in its political power bases of
Pusan, Taegu, Ulsan and Kyongsang provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
