<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Financial Authorities Plan Bank Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's financial authorities
are considering merging Radanasin Bank with financial company
Krungthai Thanakit Plc (KTT) and combining three nationalized
banks into a single entity, the Nation reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The move is to conserve bank licenses for the next few years,
the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Thailand Governor Chatumongol Sonakul revealed
Wednesday after meeting Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda
that the authorities have decided not to seek foreign partners for
Radanasin Bank.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongol said the decision was made because Radanasin has no
need to bid for the assets of the 56 closed finance companies to
be auctioned by the Financial Sector Restructuring Authority
(FRA).
</P>
<P>
"The second (FRA) decree that protects asset buyers after the
auctions should draw more bidders. Thus, the bank need not join
the bidding. It would be left doing business as usual and in the
future it would be merged with KTT if necessary," the newspaper
quoted the central bank governor as saying.
</P>
<P>
Radanasin Bank, which is capitalized at 4 billion baht (100
million U.S. dollars), was initially to bid for the assets of the
56 shut down finance companies.
</P>
<P>
KTT is to merge with seven ailing finance companies, which had
been taken over by the government.
</P>
<P>
If Radanasin Bank and KTT merge, the authorities can save one
banking license.
</P>
<P>
The Thai authorities have issued 16 banking licenses, including
three to nationalized banks -- Siam City Bank, First Bangkok City
Bank and Bangkok Metropolitan Bank.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongol said the three banks need to forge partnerships
with foreign investors. If the three are merged into a single
entity, two licenses will be returned to the Bank of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongol said Wednesday that the central bank will sell only
one license this year to ensure the government receives a fair
price for it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government Urged to Focus on Micro Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 4 (Xinhua) -- It is time for the Thai government
to turn its economic policy around to focus on micro instead of
macro economy, an economist said.
</P>
<P>
Teerana Pongmakapat, an economist of Chulalongkorn University's
economic faculty, was quoted Thursday by the Bangkok Post as
saying that the country's macroeconomy has been stabilized to a
certain extent, so the government should shift its concentration
to micro policies.
</P>
<P>
He particularly urged the government to inject liquidity to the
market.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government maintained its policy of high interest
rates in a bid to stabilize the currency. However, many local
businesses could not afford the high interest rates and suffered
from liquidity crunch.
</P>
<P>
Teerana said if the local economy contracted too much, it would
also affect the baht's value.
</P>
<P>
In the past few weeks, the government had been strongly
criticized for its policies focusing on stabilizing the
macroeconomy, and ignoring the poor and the real estate sector.
</P>
<P>
In view of this, the government has agreed to implement both
fiscal and monetary measures to help the real estate sector and
reinvigorate the sagging economy.
</P>
<P>
The objective of these measures is to inject liquidity into the
market, according to top government officials.
</P>
<P>
The agreement came after Tuesday's cabinet meeting between
government officials, led by Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, Deputy
Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi and Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanhaeminda, and senior members of the Thailand Development
Research Institute (TDRI), led by chairman Anand Panyarachun.
</P>
<P>
The government agreed with TDRI's recommendation that it give
more weight to short-term monetary measures.
</P>
<P>
Among the measures to be implemented shortly are tax incentives
to encourage loan restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The government agreed that if business corporations and their
bankers could settle their loan-restructuring schemes, more
liquidity would be available in the money market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
