<HEADLINE> Laos Agrees to Allow Thai Vehicles into Vientiane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Laos agreed to allow
Thai-registered vehicles to enter its capital Vientiane, the
Nation Thursday quoted Foreign Ministry spokesman Kobsak Chutikul
as saying.
</P>
<P>
But the spokesman did not say when the new measure would become
effective.
</P>
<P>
Kobsak said Wednesday that the agreement was reached Wednesday
at a meeting between Thai Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan and his
Lao counterpart Somsavat Lengsavad during the former's three-day
official visit to Vientiane.
</P>
<P>
The vehicles entering Vientiane needed insurance that covered
accidents in foreign countries, Kobsak said.
</P>
<P>
Laos has refused to allow Thai vehicles into the capital for
fear of traffic congestion. Thai vehicles had to park at the foot
of the Thai-Lao Friendship Bridge, which links the Lao capital
with Nongkhai province in northeastern Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Thai Interior Ministry also agreed to allow
vehicles from Laos to enter Thailand's northeastern province of
Udon Thani.
</P>
<P>
At present, vehicles from Laos can go only to Nongkhai
province.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Surin also proposed a new framework of
Thai-Lao relations called interdependence partnership towards 2003
and aimed at greater bilateral prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Thailand and Laos plan to sign four bilateral agreements
covering extradition, finance and cross-border transport when Lao
prime minister visits Bangkok later this year, Surin revealed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, U.S. Sign Investment Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh and the United States of
America have signed an investment incentive agreement to
facilitate U.S. private investment in Bangladesh, The New Nation
daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Overseas Private Investment
Corporation (OPIC) of the U.S. might provide political risk
insurance and debt financing to American companies making
long-term investment in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The agreement paved the way for the OPIC's financial support to
U.S. investors working in Bangladesh, including 375 million U.S.
dollars in financial support for U.S. company Unocal's proposed
Western Region Integrated Project.
</P>
<P>
The OPIC previously announced that it would provide 175 million
dollars in loan guarantees and 200 million dollars in political
risk insurance for the project.
</P>
<P>
Since 1971, the OPIC had supported 107.8 billion dollars worth
of investments in developing countries, and the Unocal had already
invested over 5 billion dollars in energy projects in Asia and had
implemented projects including resource development,
transportation facilities and power production, the report said.
</P>
