<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moody's Freezes Thailand's Near-term Rating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Despite the positive moves made by
the Thai government to address the economic problems, Moody's
investors service said it would not change Thailand's credit
rating in the near term.
</P>
<P>
Julia Turner, managing director for Asia Pacific corporate
ratings, said Wednesday that political stability, which is
essential as structural reforms continue, remains an uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
The policies and steps taken by the government are promising,
but the support for the government may diminish due to the pain
involved in implementation of these policies, Thursday's Bangkok
Post quoted her as saying.
</P>
<P>
Turner praised the government's efforts to encourage
transparency, reform the financial sector and attract capital
inflows.
</P>
<P>
But Thailand could take up to seven years to achieve
sustainable growth, she said, citing poor export performance,
regional instability and the worsening economies in Asia as the
reasons.
</P>
<P>
Moody's currently assigns Thailand a Ba1 rating, one step below
investment grade.
</P>
<P>
Investors closely monitor credit ratings in pricing new debt
issues, with poorly-rated issuers forced to pay higher interest
for borrowings in the international market.
</P>
<P>
Thai Finance Ministry is expected to issue up to 5 billion U.S.
dollars in global bonds over the next few years, with the first
lot scheduled over the next few months.
</P>
<P>
Analysts expect the new bonds to be priced 300 to 350 basis
points or about 9 to 9.5 percent over U.S. treasuries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
