<HEADLINE> S. Asia Shouldn't Waste Money on Arms Race: Hasina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina Wednesday said countries of poverty-stricken South Asia
"should not waste money in an arms race creating a tense situation
in the region", according to press reports Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We don't believe in arms race, we want peace... We are deeply
concerned over the situation created in the region," she said
while addressing army officers Wednesday at Bandarban Cantonment,
about 260 kilometers southeast of here.
</P>
<P>
The recent nuclear tests conducted by India and Pakistan had
created anxiety in Bangladesh because of her geographical
location, she told the army officers.
</P>
<P>
She asked members of the armed forces to remain alert, saying
"if needed, the defense system should be further consolidated and
our strategy should be changed in a changed situation."
</P>
<P>
"What is the justification of the arms race when the whole
world is striving for peace?" Hasina asked.
</P>
<P>
"The two countries (India and Pakistan) can solve all the
problems through negotiation," she said.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government would try not to let the situation
aggravate further in the region, Hasina said. "If needed, I will
visit the countries for the sake of peace."
</P>
<P>
The money spent in the arms race could be spend for the poor
people of the region, she said. "This will help improve the
condition of the distressed people." 
</P>
