<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Economic Solution Depends on Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The solution to Indonesia's
economic crisis depends largely on a solution to the political
uncertainty, an independent think tank was quoted by local press
Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
In a discussion here Wednesday, the Econit Advisory Group said
that unless Indonesia elects a new credible government, the
country's economy would soon collapse.
</P>
<P>
Plunging foreign exchange reserves, the ballooning budget
deficit and the severe lack of capital inflow are all serious
threats to the economy's ability to survive the economic crisis,
Econit said.
</P>
<P>
"We must have a government which is credible both domestically
and internationally," said the group's senior economist Rizal
Ramli.
</P>
<P>
Econit expects the country's economy to contract 10 percent
this year against an average growth rate of 7 percent before the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"This would cause additional unemployment of around 20
million," Rizal said.
</P>
<P>
President Habibie, who has promised a general election sometime
next year, seems to have started gaining international confidence.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the World Bank said Wednesday that it had
resumed a 225 million U.S. dollars loan to reduce poverty in
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) Asia-Pacific Director
Hubert Neiss has also said that Indonesia had an impressive
economic team led by Coordinating Minister for Economy, Finance
and Industry Ginandjar Kartasasmita. 
</P>
</TEXT>
