<HEADLINE> American Countries Join Hands against Social Evils </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The 34 member countries of the
Organization of American States (OAS) Wednesday expressed their
determination to close ranks in the fight against drug, terrorism,
corruption and poverty.
</P>
<P>
The Caracas Statement, issued at the conclusion of the 28th OAS
annual meeting, calls on all members to enhance regional
cooperation, particularly on preventing the consumption,
production and transportation of drugs.
</P>
<P>
Mutual respect, dialogue and regional cooperation are the basis
of drug-fighting, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers or their representatives attending the
three-day meeting have also agreed that regional poverty is the
biggest obstacle to peace and development, and that education is
the precondition for eradicating poverty and improving regional
politics, economy and culture.
</P>
<P>
The statement also puts forth an action plan for prevention and
eradication of terrorism and corruption. "Corruption hurts our
public institutions, degrades moral values and hinder social
progress."
</P>
<P>
These efforts will pave the way for regional integration and
protection of democracy.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also passed a resolution condemning India and
Pakistan for their nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
Several issues divided the delegates, including a recent
U.S. drug sting in Mexico and a threat by Trinidad and Tobago to
withdraw from the Inter-American Convention on Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Mexico conflicted on Operation Casablanca, a drug
sting carried out partially on Mexican soil. Mexico has launched a
formal protest with Washington after the operation was made public.
</P>
<P>
Guatemala will host the 1999 assembly of the OAS, which is
headquartered in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
