<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New U.S. Census Board Members Take Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Members of the new board formed
to monitor "Census 2000" in the United States took office
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The eight-member group will observe the effort to conduct a
national head count and help resolve potential disputes over how
that can best be done.
</P>
<P>
"Accuracy is a surprisingly complicated issue," said David W.
Murray of the Statistical Assessment Service, a Washington-based
think tank.
</P>
<P>
Murray, a republican-appointed board member, called the 2000
effort "a census at risk."
</P>
<P>
An estimated four million people were missed in the 1990
census. In an effort to reduce that error, statisticians
recommended using a system called "sampling" to improve the count
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The first 90 percent of people would be counted by traditional
methods and the sampling would be used to help account for the
remaining 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
That plan has become a highly controversial issue.
</P>
<P>
Most of those missed in 1990 were minorities and residents in
large cities, groups that usually vote democratic.
</P>
<P>
Since census figures are used to distribute seats in the House
of Representatives and redistrict political boundaries,
republicans fear the result would be losing republican seats in
the Congress and state and local governing bodies. They contend
that sampling is little more than unconstitutional guessing.
</P>
<P>
Democrats, meanwhile, insist sampling is the best way to get an
accurate count of people who often do not want to cooperate with
government.
</P>
<P>
Murray said the census must be done efficiently, but not in a
way that abandons the U.S. Constitution's mandate for accuracy.
</P>
<P>
Everett Ehrlich, a former undersecretary of commerce and a
democratic appointee to the board, responded that the country
needs an "accurate count, not just of those who can be found or
who answered the mail that day ... but of all Americans."
</P>
<P>
The choice, Ehrlich said, is between a census where most people
are counted one by one and the rest estimated, even if that last
group is considered "fuzzy." Or a census where most are counted
and the rest are simply not counted.
</P>
<P>
Ohio State Treasurer J. Kenneth Blackwell and former
Representative Tony Coelho, a democrat, are the board's republican
and democratic co-chairmen.
</P>
<P>
The opening meeting Wednesday came a day after President Bill
Clinton promoted census sampling in a Texas speech.
</P>
<P>
"If we are really going to strengthen our country and prepare
for this new century, we have to have a full and accurate picture
of who we are as a people and where we live," Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
