<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Researchers Link Unusual Dementia to Gene Flaw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Scientists from Seattle, the
U.S., have identified a gene associated with a disease that is
similar to Alzheimers.
</P>
<P>
Symptoms of the disease typically begin in the early 50s.
Sometimes the symptoms result in difficult behavior and at other
times it causes problems with muscle control.
</P>
<P>
It is not an Alzheimer's gene, but it has implications for
Alzheimer's disease and other disorders.
</P>
<P>
Reporting their findings in the June edition of the Annals of
Neurology, the researchers claim the gene is yet another link to
Alzheimers and may help further understanding of several other
diseases.
</P>
<P>
It is the second Alzheimer's linked gene found in recent years
by researchers at the Seattle-based Veterans Affairs Medical
Center and the University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
In the new research, the scientists have found that patients'
brain cells with the unusual dementia are filled with abnormal
tangles of protein filaments. Yet they lacked the amyloid protein
plaque that clogs the brains of Alzheimer's patients.
</P>
<P>
Analyzing the DNA of 21 patients from two families, the
researchers discovered that the villain is a defect in a gene on
chromosome 17 called Tau.
</P>
<P>
The research opens a new path for exploration of possible drug
treatment, not only for Alzheimers but for several other illnesses.
</P>
<P>
Some patients with the gene flaw have schizophrenic-like
delusions early in the disease. Or they may become argumentative
and short-tempered, often talking loudly and swearing in public.
</P>
<P>
Others have some symptoms of Parkinson's disease, including
muscle rigidity and slow movements. Or they have severe muscle
loss and weakness, similar to patients with amyotrophic lateral
sclerosis (Lou Gehrig's disease). After several years, many lose
the ability to speak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
