<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Type of Pheasant Discovered in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- About 1,500 brown-eared pheasants
have been discovered in the forested area near Mt. Huanglong in
northern Shaanxi province, northwest China.
</P>
<P>
According to the provincial wildlife administration, these
brown-eared pheasants live in a 30,000-hectare area.
</P>
<P>
The pheasant is one of China's rare bird species and was
thought to have become extinct because of large-scale logging
during and after the Song Dynasty (960-1279).
</P>
<P>
The pheasant was first sighted in nearby Shanxi Province in
1965, and four zones have been set up there to provide shelter and
protection for about 8,000 pheasants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
