<HEADLINE> Yunnan to Invest More in Highway Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan Province
will significantly increase its investment in highway construction
this year.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan's total investment in highway construction this year has
been budgeted at more than seven billion yuan, about twice the
combined figure for the previous two years.
</P>
<P>
A provincial official has said that Yunnan will spend a total
of more than 26 billion yuan in highway construction in the
1996-2000 period, as against 9.6 billion yuan for the 40 years
prior to 1995.
</P>
<P>
Abundant in natural resources, Yunnan has remained
underdeveloped partly because of backward transportation
conditions.
</P>
<P>
However, as China's economy reform deepens, Yunnan has steadily
and significantly increased its input into road construction. Its
highway construction spending totaled 7.6 billion yuan in the
1996-1997 period, as compared to 7.1 billion yuan for the five
years from 1991 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year Yunnan had built highways totalling
73,800 km in length, in addition to another 30,000 km of rural
highways.
</P>
<P>
In the remaining years of this century, Yunnan will mainly
invest in construction of expressways and other high-grade
highways, including one linking this provincial capital
with Bangkok, the provincial official said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Yunnan has applied for loans from overseas banks
and international financial institutions to help fund its highway
construction program.
</P>
<P>
Funds will also be raised through leasing the operation right
of highways to overseas enterprises, the official added.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan will have completed the construction of a complete
highway network linking it with neighboring provinces and
countries by the end of this century, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
