<HEADLINE> Russia Threatens to Withdraw Peace Force From Abkhazia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian First Deputy Foreign
Minister Boris Pastukhov warned the Georgian government and the
Abkhazian authorities that Russia may withdraw its peace-keeping
force from Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
If there is no progress in negotiating the conflict between the
two sides, and if they continue to spread rumors about the Russian
peace-keeping force, Russia will withdraw its forces from
Abkhazia, said Pastukhov at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
In response to accusations and rumors about the Russian peace
force, Pastukhov said a potentially large-scale war was prevented
recently because of the presence of Russian peace-keeping troops.
</P>
<P>
The troops prevented the transport of heavy weapons and a large
number of troops to Abkhazia, he said. And the Russian camps have
been used as safe havens for civilians during the conflict.
</P>
<P>
On June 2, six Abkhazian police were killed by land mines in
the Ghali region. Pastukhov said that President Eduard
Shevardnarzde and Abkhazian leader Vladislav Ardzinba believed the
incident was intended to undermine the peace agreement signed on
May 25.
</P>
<P>
Some people do not want to see a settlement of the conflict and
thy want to intensify the situation, Pastukhov added.
</P>
<P>
The conflict between the Georgian government force and the
Abkhazian militias began in July, 1992, when Abkhazia proclaimed
itself as an independent state.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, several thousand Russian troops went into Abkhazia to
keep the peace. The mandate for the peace-keeping force expires on
July 31, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
