<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Delighted by Grain Circulation System Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Following three years of straight
grain price declines, once-disheartened Chinese farmers have
eventually begun to smile again.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, grain prices across China have shown handsome rises
since the start of this month. In east China's Zhejiang, central
China's Hubei and many other provinces, price hikes have ranged
from five to 10 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Grain officials said they expect grain prices to go up further
in the remaining months of this year, and the overall increase rate
to exceed 10 percent on a year-on-year basis.
</P>
<P>
The encouraging price rises have come directly from China's
grain circulation reform, officially launched in May to raise
farmers' incomes and stabilize grain prices, experts note.
</P>
<P>
China has posted continuous bumper grain harvests since 1995,
with output hitting 490 million tons in 1997, a figure that has
enabled China to meet the target of 400 kg of grain per capita
each year.
</P>
<P>
However, grain surpluses have occurred in many parts of China
due to irrational distribution structures as low and
mediocre-quality grain makes up the bulk of the country's total
grain production.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, many major grain-producing areas have encountered
great difficulties in selling their grain and seen prices decline
steadily year by year. The situation has been further compounded by
hostile price cuts among competitive marketers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
