<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Delighted by Grain Circulation System Reform (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To solve the problem, the Chinese State Council decided to
overhaul its grain circulation system in late April. The nucleus
of the reform package is to protect farmers' enthusiasm to grow
rice by procuring grain at profitable prices and make grain firms
more market-oriented and economically accountable.
</P>
<P>
In just two months, Hubei, Hunan, Jiangxi, Guangdong,
Guangxi and many other provinces, municipalities and autonomous
regions have beefed up their efforts to regulate and standardize
the grain market.
</P>
<P>
Wang Chunzheng, deputy minister of the State Development
Planning Commission, said that different regions should set grain
prices on the basis of balancing the interests of both grain
producers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
In Hubei, Hunan and Jiangxi consumers have reacted calmly to
grain price increases averaging nearly 10 percent so far this
year. Official figures indicate that urban Chinese residents spend
an average of 40 yuan (about five US dollars) on grain consumption
each month.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zhuping, governor of Hubei Province, said that the
state-owned grain enterprises represent the hardest nuts to crack
in China's grain system reform. The 250,000 workers in Hubei's
state-owned grain enterprises, for example, sell an average of
only 20,000 km of grain each per year.
</P>
<P>
At least half of these workers must be diverted to other jobs
over the next three years, Jiang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-U.S. Mutual Respect Is Growing, Says Former U.S. National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Although United States headlines
imply there is friction in the Sino-U.S. relationship, the truth
is that there is growing mutual respect between both the leaders
of the two countries and among the people at the grass roots
level, says former U.S. National Security Adviser Robert
C. McFarlane.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin's visit to the United States last
fall was a "watershed event" which has led to a steady improvement
in Sino-U.S. relations, said McFarlane, who was President Ronald
Reagan's national security adviser between 1983 and 1985.
</P>
<P>
The agreement between Jiang and U.S. President Bill Clinton to
establish a "constructive strategic partnership," represents U.S.
recognition that as great powers, China and the United States both
share important responsibilities to consult with each other on how
together they can help solve problems which could upset stability
in any part of the world, McFarlane said in response to a written
question by Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
At this moment for example, McFarlane said, "it will be
important for them to focus during their talks on the situation in
South Asia with a view towards reaching agreement on measures they
can take together to restore stability."
</P>
<P>
President Clinton is scheduled to make his reciprocal visit to
China later this month.
</P>
<P>
McFarlane said that already the two countries have cooperated in
moderating the damage from the recent currency turmoil in Asia.
"China's restraint in not devaluing its currency has helped to
stabilize the situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Perhaps, he said, the greatest potential for an early
demonstration of the importance and potential of
Sino-U.S. cooperation would be for the two leaders to agree during
their meetings to focus on how together they can contribute to the
restoration of stability in South Asia, and then to organizing the
necessary investment funds to stimulate growth in the economies of
the region so as to relieve the root of turmoil.
</P>
<P>
"As globalization gathers momentum, it will be more and more
important for China and the United States to coordinate their
economic policies so as to reduce the potential for turmoil in
trading relationships, and to avoid a spiral of competitive
devaluations in Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is also potential for China and the U.S. to cooperate in
the development of the Russian energy resources in Siberia so as
to prevent any ultimate competition for energy between Japan and
China," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
