<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli, Syrian Officials Meet in Houston </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Syrian officials
have made three-day informal discussions on long-stalled peace
talks this week at Rice University in Houston, Texas, an official
at the university said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time in two years that the two countries have
had high-level contacts about the peace process. But the meetings,
which began Monday, were not described as "direct negotiations."
</P>
<P>
"I want to underscore that these deliberations did not
constitute negotiations between the parties, but we had this
unique gathering of individuals to discuss it with a view toward
getting some policy formulations to decision makers," said Edward
Djerejian, director of the university's James Baker Institute for
Public Policy.
</P>
<P>
Djerejian, who initiated the meetings, said about 20 of "the
very top people" in the Mideast policy world attended the
sessions, including Syria's ambassador to Washington Walid Mualem,
and Uzi Arad, foreign policy adviser to Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu. U.S Assistant Secretary of State Martin Indyk
and former Secretary of State James Baker also attended the
sessions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
