<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO Puts Global Fish Business at 250 Bln Dlrs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- World fish business is
estimated at over 250 billion U.S. dollars a year, according to
the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO).
</P>
<P>
The figure obtained here Wednesday includes fish production
valued at 120 billion dollars, plus trade and value-addition on
the way to the consumer, FAO said in a study released at the
on-going meeting on fish trade in Bremen, Germany, on June 3-6.
</P>
<P>
Fish is an important food product exported by developing
countries, coming well before coffee, banana and tea, the study
quoted FAO fisheries expert Erhard Ruckes as saying.
</P>
<P>
Fish exports by developing countries rose to 17.2 billion
dollars in 1996 from 5.2 billion dollars in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Developed countries account for more than 80 percent of total
fish imports, with Japan topping the list, followed by the United
States and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The study sees recent changes by importers in quality control
measures on fishery products as a new challenge to the developing
world.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the changes, countries like India, Bangladesh,
Madagascar, Kenya, Tanzania, Mozambique and Uganda have been
facing difficulties in exporting their fish products since 1997,
according to FAO.
</P>
<P>
Because of eco-labeling, which requires that fish produce
from a sustainably managed resource, small-scale fishermen in the
developing countries could be disadvantageous as it is difficult
for them to certify their fish production, FAO added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Iraq Has Much Progress to Make to Get </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- If Iraq wants sanctions to
be lifted, it has a lot of progress to make, Bill Richardson, the
U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Richardson made the remarks after the morning session of a
special Security Council briefing given by Butler Richard,
executive chairman of the United Nations Special Commission
(UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
"UNSCOM has dealt a devastating blow to Iraq's credibility. I
think Iraq has had a bad day here," Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
According U.N. sources, Butler Richard, in his briefing, had
demonstrated a pattern of concealment of missile production and
showed how, in 1991, Iraq said it had destroyed its ballistic
missiles but surveillance photos showed no activity at the site.
</P>
<P>
"There is some disturbing information about propellants that
lead us to believe that in the missile program this is serious,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said UNSCOM had produced documents, charts and
photos that catalogue the gap and inconsistencies of Iraq's
disarmament claims.
</P>
<P>
Iraq needs a clean bill of health from UNSCOM and the
International Atomic Energy Agency before the Security Council can
consider lifting the sanctions in force since Iraq invaded Kuwait
in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright: U.S. to Make New Initiative for Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said Wednesday that the United States would make a new
initiative to try to break the current dilemma in the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
She was answering a question at a news conference about a
statement Wednesday by U.S. ambassador to Israel Edward Walker
that Washington would decide within days whether to press ahead
with a peace initiative that has faltered because of Israel's
objection to a U.S. proposal on Israeli troops' withdrawal from
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Albright said the United States would continue talks on the
peace process so long as they were "constructive." But she said
when she felt that was not the case, she would be "the first one
that is going to declare that they are not."
</P>
<P>
"I will make that determination at the time. I'm not going to
give it a specific time frame, but soon," she added. "This is not
something that's going to go on much longer."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister Jawad al-Anani
disclosed in Amman that U.S. Undersecretary of State Thomas
Pickering had asked Arab states to delay announcement of a
proposed summit to give the U.S. initiative more time to succeed.
</P>
<P>
"The Americans estimate the period between one week to 10
days," Anani said.
</P>
<P>
Albright and her aides have repeatedly said that if current
peace efforts stalled completely, they would announce the end of
the U.S. initiative in its present form. 
</P>
</TEXT>
