<HEADLINE> U.S. Chamber Urges China's MFN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Chamber of Commerce
Wednesday said the Clinton administration's effort to extend
normal trade relations to China is the right step for business and
consumers, and urged Congress to support the president's decision.
</P>
<P>
"The evidence is clear -- a stable U.S.-China commercial
framework will open markets for U.S. exports and generate more jobs
for American workers," said Willard Workman, chamber vice president
for international.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton proposed earlier Wednesday the renewal
of China's Most-Favored Nation (MFN) trade status for another
year. He said that it is vital for the United States to maintain
normal trade relationship with that Asian country.
</P>
<P>
Workman said, "The United States needs to maintain bipartisan
support for a clear, credible and consistent long-term China
policy. That's why Congress should support the president's
decision."
</P>
<P>
He warned that if MFN is not renewed, U.S. exports to China and
corresponding American business and jobs will be at risk. "We
cannot allow that to happen."
</P>
<P>
The MFN status allows goods to be sold in the U.S. with normal
tariffs. It is extended to most nations and was first granted to
China in 1979. The annual renewal of China's MFN has become an
opportunity to debate the U.S. China policy, a controversial issue
in the United States for years.
</P>
<P>
Although Congress has gone along with the Administration for
extending the trade status to China, the heated debate would
usually pick up the issues of human rights and proliferation.
</P>
<P>
"A policy of engagement with China is our national interests,"
said Workman. "And this policy has worked. It promotes American
interests on issues of vital importance, including security,
non-proliferation, the rule of law, and human rights as well as
trade."
</P>
<P>
He noted that American companies and workers have a huge stake
in U.S.-China trade relations. In 1997, the United States exported
approximately 12.8 billion U.S. dollars in goods and services to
China. These exports support hundreds of thousands of high-wage
American jobs.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Chamber of Commerce is the world's largest business
federation representing more than 3 million businesses and
organizations of every size, sector and region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
