<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Government Urges Public to Prepare for Disasters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States government
Wednesday called for local communities' preparations for disasters
before they strike.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) asked cities,
towns and counties across the country to form partnerships among
local business and civic leaders to prepare for disaster.
</P>
<P>
"I have seen too much devastation in the last five years; I
have seen too many lives lost and too many dreams destroyed,"
James Lee Witt, director of the FEMA, told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to change the way we deal with disaster," he
said. "We must put an end to the repetitive cycle of damage and
repair, damage and repair. We cannot continue to do the same
things over and over again."
</P>
<P>
Witt said natural disasters are becoming more severe, more
damaging and more costly. The government paid out 2.8 billion U.S.
dollars from 1978 to 1998 to deal with recurring flood losses
alone. In the same 20-year period, the agency has spent 20 billion
dollars overall on disaster recovery efforts, much of it toward
the end of the period.
</P>
<P>
He said natural disasters have killed 181 people this year
alone.
</P>
<P>
Under the disaster preparedness proposal, dubbed Project
Impact, Witt said, 30 million U.S. dollars in seed money is
earmarked for the effort this year, with 50 million dollars
requested for the fiscal year starting next October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
