<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Train Crash Still a Puzzle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ESCHEDE, Germany, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The reason for the
worst-ever German train crash which occurred Wednesday morning
still remains unclear after the driver of the high-speed train was
uninjured and only knew of the crash afterwards.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 people were killed and 300 others injured when
the InterCity Express (ICE) derailed and slammed into a road
bridge near a small rail station of the northeastern German town
of Eschede at 11:10 a.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Investigators told reporters that the front engine of the train
had become detained from its 14 carriages and went on at high
speed towards the rail station. The driver only knew of the
accident after he felt a slight jerk and exercised the emergency
brake to stop the engine.
</P>
<P>
Earlier media reports said the train, en route from Munich to
Hamburg, was derailed after hitting a car which had plunged onto
the rail tracks after a road accident on the bridge. But this
scenario cannot explain why the engine remains intact.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman said later the automobile concerned had
actually parked on the bridge and fallen onto the ground after the
bridge collapsed due to the train crash.
</P>
<P>
German rail authorities said that there were still no signs of
a technical defect on the train or on the track.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, about 1,000 rescue workers are still busy on the
scene to try to retrieve bodies and possible survivors trapped
under the train wreckage. With evening setting in, they are still
unable to reach two of the coaches wedged under the remains of the
bridge.
</P>
<P>
According to government officials, German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl has broken off a German-Italian summit in the Italian city of
Bologna and will return to Germany later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
German President Roman Herzog and British Prime Minister Tony
Blair meanwhile have sent condolences to the victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
