<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Parliament Chief Urges Bonn to Resolve War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Greek Parliament President Apostolos
Kaklamanis Wednesday urged Germany to resolve the issue of Greek
claims of wartime reparations from Germany as well as clarify its
stance over the repayment of a wartime loan taken out by the Nazis
during the World War II occupation of Greece.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a delegation from the Bundestag's Legal Committee,
Kaklamanis said that Germany should reconsider the issue of
reparations and the loan so as not to cause problems to the good
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Last year, a court in the central Greek city of Livadeia
ordered Germany to pay 32 million U.S. dollars in reparations to
the village of Distomo, where 214 residents were killed by Nazi
soldiers on June 10, 1944, but the German government refused to
comply with the Greek ruling.
</P>
<P>
The German delegation, currently in Greece for talks on legal
and European policy issues, is also expected to meet with Greek
Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos, Public Order Minister George
Romeos and other Greek government officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
