<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Falls Against Mark, Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell against the
German mark Wednesday in New York as markets in Russia got more
stablized.
</P>
<P>
The dollar slipped against the Japanese yen again on continued
speculation that the Group of Seven major industrialized nations
could produce joint action to prop up the yen.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 138.75 yen,
down slightly from 138.83 yen from late Tuesday. The dollar also
was changing hands at 1.7710 marks, down from 1.7806.
</P>
<P>
Russia's stock market has been rebounding, rising 12 percent
Tuesday and nearly 9 percent Wednesday. The ruble has also been
steady in recent days.
</P>
<P>
Traders abandoned the dollar as a safe haven Wednesday and
bought marks and other European currencies.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Tuesday: 1.4757 Swiss francs, down from 1.4808; 5.9345 French
francs, down from 5.9735; 1,743.55 Italian lire, down from
1,755.00; and 1.4527 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4528.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6399 U.S. dollars, up from
1.6393 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
