<HEADLINE> Snow Falls in S. Dakota, Heat Strikes South U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- More than half a foot of snow
fell on mountainous areas in western South Dakota Wednesday
morning, but heat struck the southern part of the United States a
day earlier.
</P>
<P>
The thunderstorms-led cold air across the Plains brought up to
seven inches of snow to the western part of the state, the
second-latest snowfall ever recorded in Rapid City in the Black
Hills. The previous snow was recorded on June 13, 1969, the
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Up to three inches of snow also fell on the adjacent Plains and
in the eastern end of the state.
</P>
<P>
In Rapid City, temperature fell to a record low of 32 degrees
(zero degree centigrade), knocking one degree off the former
record for the date, set in 1951. Parts of northern Nebraska also
had lows in the low 30s.
</P>
<P>
However, heat records fell across western Texas Tuesday. At
Wichita Falls, Texas, it was 109 degrees (42.7 degree centigrade),
surpassing the previous high reading of 101 (38 degree centigrade)
on the day in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
