<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Condemns Terrorist Attacks in Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States condemns
terrorist attacks in Tehran, the State Department said Wednesday
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that the outlawed Iranian opposition group
the Mujahedeen Khalq claimed responsibility for a blast Tuesday in
Tehran, that killed at least three people and injured six.
</P>
<P>
"The United States government strongly condemns the terrorist
attacks in Tehran.... We offer our condolences to the victims,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The United States government reiterates its strong
condemnation of any and all terrorist attacks wherever they
occur," it added.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say Washington's public condemnation against
Mujahedeen shows the Clinton administration intended to open
dialogue with the Iranian government. Behind the scenes, the
Mujahedeen's allies continue to run offices in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
