<DOCNO> XIE19980604.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Seek Common Ground to Defuse Nuclear Tensions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.S. administration
official said Wednesday that Washington will seek common ground at
a Geneva meeting to reverse the deteriorating situation in South
Asia following nuclear tests by India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
But, he said, the United States will not press other permanent
members of the Security Council to impose sanctions on the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Karl Inderfurth, assistant secretary of state for South Asian
affairs, told a Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee hearting
that the Geneva meeting, scheduled on Thursday, was seeking to
"defuse the current tensions in South Asia following last
month's nuclear test by India and Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
He said the United States would not press other permanent
members of the Security Council -- Britain, China, France and
Russia, who will attend the Geneva meeting, -- to impose sanctions
on the two countries, which he said would not be productive.
</P>
<P>
Inderfurth told the panel that the United States would "firmly
reject" any move to bring India and Pakistan into the existing
club of the existing five nuclear powers, spelled out in the
nonproliferation treaty.
</P>
<P>
"There is no disposition to reward any nation for blasting its
way into the nuclear-state category," he said.
</P>
<P>
Inderfurth also said both India and Pakistan may have
overstated the number of nuclear tests they conducted, and the
variety of devices they tested.
</P>
<P>
India has claimed five tests, Pakistan six. But Inderfurth said
the two countries likely exploded "less than they said" and that
the precise number was still being determined by scrutinizing
seismic and other data. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
